title:
USS Alabama
(battleship)
desc: One of two surviving South Dakota-class battleships, Alabama was commissioned in 1942 and spent forty months in active service in World War II's Pacific theater, earning nine battle stars over twenty-six engagements with the Japanese.[8]

title: Apalachicola Fort Site
desc: Spain established this wattle and daub blockhouse on the Chattahoochee River in 1690, attempting to maintain influence among the Lower Creek Indians. It was used for one year, and destroyed by the Spanish when they abandoned it.[9]

title: Barton Hall
desc: This structure, built in 1840, is described by the National Park Service as an "unusually sophisticated" Greek Revival style plantation house. The interior contains a stairway that ascends in a series of double flights and bridge-like landings to an observatory on the rooftop that offers views of the plantation.[10][11]

title: Bethel Baptist Church, Parsonage, and Guard House
desc: This church served as the headquarters for the Alabama Christian Movement for Human Rights, an organization active in the Civil Rights Movement, from 1956 to 1961. It focused on legal and nonviolent direct action against segregated accommodations, transportation, schools and employment discrimination.[12]

title: Bottle Creek Site
desc: This archaeological site contains eighteen mounds from the Mississippian cultural period. Located on Mound Island within the Mobile-Tensaw river delta, the site was occupied between AD 1250 and 1550. Scholars believe that it functioned as a social, political, religious, and trade center for the Mobile Delta region and the central Gulf Coast.[13]

title: Brown Chapel A.M.E. Church
desc: This church was a starting point for the Selma to Montgomery marches in 1965, and it played a major role in the events that led to the adoption of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The national reaction to Selma's "Bloody Sunday March" is widely credited with making the passage of the Voting Rights Act politically viable in the United States Congress.[14]

title: City Hall
desc: The Italianate style Old City Hall and Southern Market in Mobile was completed in 1857. This building exemplifies the 19th-century American trend toward structures that served multiple civic functions.[15]

title: Henry D. Clayton House
desc: This was the home of anti-trust legislator Henry De Lamar Clayton, Jr. He was the author of the Clayton Antitrust Act, an act that prohibited particular types of conduct that were deemed to not be in the best interest of a competitive market. He was appointed as a Federal District Judge in 1914, and became recognized as an advocate for judicial reform.[16]

title: J.L.M. Curry Home
desc: This was the home of educator Jabez Lamar Monroe Curry. He played a large role in the expansion and improvement of the public school system and the establishment of training schools for teachers throughout the South.[17]

title: Dexter Avenue Baptist Church
desc: Martin Luther King, Jr. was the pastor of this church from 1954 to 1960. The Montgomery Improvement Association, which was headed by Dr. King, had its headquarters in the church and organized the Montgomery Bus Boycott from this site in 1955.[18]

title:
USS Drum
(submarine)
desc: Launched on May 12, 1941, this was the first of the Gato-class submarines completed before World War II. It represents what was the standard design for American fleet submarines at the beginning of that war. The USS Drum sank fifteen Japanese ships and earned twelve battle stars.[19]

title: Episcopal Church of the Nativity
desc: This Gothic Revival church was built in 1859, and is considered by the National Park Service as one of the most pristine examples of Ecclesiastical Gothic architecture in the South. It is also one of the least-altered structures designed by architect Frank Wills.[20]

title: First Confederate Capitol
desc: Delegates from six seceding Southern states met here on February 4, 1861. On February 8, they adopted a "Constitution for the Provisional Government of the Confederate States of America." Jefferson Davis was inaugurated on the west portico on February 18. The Congress of the Confederate States met here until May 22, 1861, when the capital moved to Richmond, Virginia.[21]

title: Fort Mitchell Site
desc: Fort Mitchell represents three periods of interaction with Native Americans. The first period is the martial aspect of Manifest Destiny, when the Creek Indian Nation was defeated and forced to concede land.; the second represents the Indian Factory; the last concerns U.S. government attempts to honor treaty obligations.[22]

title: Fort Morgan
desc: Fort Morgan was completed in 1834 and was used by Confederate forces during the Battle of Mobile Bay. This battle resulted in the Union Navy's Admiral David Farragut taking Mobile Bay and sealing off the Port of Mobile to Confederate shipping.[23]

title: Fort Toulouse Site
desc: Fort Toulouse served as the easternmost outpost of colonial French Louisiana. It was established in 1717 at the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers, and was abandoned in 1763, after the Treaty of Paris. Andrew Jackson reestablished a fort here in 1814 following his defeat of the Creek Nation at the Battle of Horseshoe Bend.[24]

title: Foster Auditorium
desc: The Alabama National Guard, Federal marshals, and U.S. Attorney General Nicholas Katzenbach escorted Vivian Malone past Alabama governor George C. Wallace during his infamous "Stand In The Schoolhouse Door" in front of this building in 1963. This was the first step in desegregating the University of Alabama and is seen as an important event in the Civil Rights Movement in the United States.[25]

title: Gaineswood
desc: This Greek Revival mansion was designated a NHL because it is considered one of the most unusual examples of that architectural style in the United States. It was built over the course of eighteen years by amateur architect and planter Nathan Bryan Whitfield. It is one of the few Greek Revival homes that features the Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian orders of architecture.[26]

title: Government Street Presbyterian Church
desc: This church was built in 1836 and is one of the oldest and least-altered Greek Revival church buildings in the United States. The architectural design is by James Gallier, James Dakin, and Charles Dakin.[27]

title: Ivy Green
desc: This site is where deaf and blind Helen Keller was born and learned to communicate, with the aid of her teacher and constant companion, Anne Sullivan.[28]

title: Kenworthy Hall
desc: This plantation house was completed in 1860 and is one of the best preserved examples of Richard Upjohn's distinctive asymmetrical Italian villa style. It is the only surviving residential example of Upjohn's Italian villa style that was especially designed to suit the Southern climate and the plantation lifestyle.[29]

title: Montgomery (snagboat)
desc: One of the few surviving steam-powered sternwheelers in the United States, it is one of two surviving United States Army Corps of Engineers snagboats. It was built in 1925 and played a major role in building the Alabamaâ€“Tombigbeeâ€“Tennessee River Project.[30]

title: Montgomery Union Station and Trainshed
desc: Constructed in 1898, this is an example of late 19th-century commercial architecture. It served as the focal point of transportation into Montgomery. The train shed is significant in that it shows the adaptation of bridge-building techniques to shelter structures, an important step in the history of American engineering.[31]

title: Moundville Site
desc: Moundville was first settled in the 10th century and represents a major period of Mississippian culture in the Southern United States. It acted as the center for a southerly diffusion of this culture toward the Gulf Coast.[32] It was the second largest site of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in Illinois.

title: Neutral Buoyancy Space Simulator
desc: This structure was built in 1955 to provide a simulated zero-gravity environment in which engineers, designers, and astronauts could perform the various phases of research needed to gain firsthand knowledge concerning design and operation problems associated with working in space. It contributed significantly to the United States space program, especially Project Gemini, the Apollo program, Skylab, and the Space Shuttle.[33]

title: Edmund Pettus Bridge
desc: This bridge across the Alabama River is noted for being the site of a bloody encounter during a civil rights march in 1965, an event influential in the passage of that year's Voting Rights Act.[35]

title: Propulsion and Structural Test Facility
desc: This site was built in 1957 by the Army Ballistic Missile Agency and was the primary center responsible for the development of large vehicles and rocket propulsion systems. The Saturn Family of launch vehicles was developed here under the direction of Wernher von Braun. The Saturn V remains the most powerful launch vehicle ever brought to operational status, from a height, weight and payload standpoint.[36]

title: Redstone Test Stand
desc: This steel frame structure was built in 1953 and is the oldest static firing facility at the Marshall Space Flight Center. It was important in the development of the Jupiter-C and Mercury/Redstone vehicles that launched the first U.S. satellite and the first U.S. manned spaceflight.[37]

title: St. Andrew's Church
desc: This small Carpenter Gothic church, with wooden buttresses, was built in 1853, and shows the influence of 19th-century architectural leader Richard Upjohn. It is considered one of the Southeast's outstanding examples of the picturesque movement in American church building.[38]

title: Saturn V Dynamic Test Stand
desc: Built in 1964 to conduct mechanical and vibrational tests on the fully assembled Saturn V rocket; major problems capable of causing failure of the vehicle were discovered and corrected here.[39]

title: Saturn V Launch Vehicle
desc: This was the prototype for the Saturn V launch vehicle and was the first Saturn V constructed by the Marshall Space Flight Center under the direction of Dr. Wernher von Braun. It served as the test vehicle for the Saturn support facilities at the Marshall Space Flight Center.[40]

title: Sixteenth Street Baptist Church
desc: This church was used as a meeting place, training center, and as a departure point for marches during the Civil Rights Movement. It was the site of a bombing by the Ku Klux Klan on September 16, 1963, in which four young girls were killed and twenty-two others were injured.[41]

title: Sloss Blast Furnaces
desc: Built from 1881 to 1882, this is the oldest remaining blast furnace in the state. Its NHL designation represents Alabama's early 20th-century preeminence in the production of pig iron and cast iron, an example of a post-Civil War effort to industrialize the agrarian South.[42]

title: Swayne Hall, Talladega College
desc: Swayne Hall was built in 1857 as a Baptist men's college. Following the American Civil War, it became a part of Talladega College, Alabama's oldest private, historically black, liberal arts college.[43]

title: Tuskegee Institute
desc: One of the best known African American universities in the United States, Tuskegee was founded by Booker T. Washington in 1881. It began with a curriculum designed to provide industrial and vocational education to African Americans and featured such acclaimed educators as George Washington Carver.[44] Tuskegee Institute is both a National Historic Landmark and a National Historic Site.

title: Wilson Dam
desc: Wilson Dam, on the Tennessee River, was built between 1918 and 1925 by the United States Army Corps of Engineers and later came under the control of the Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA). It is the oldest of TVA's hydroelectric dams.[45]

title: Yuchi Town Site
desc: This archaeological site was occupied by the Apalachicola and Yuchi tribes. During the 17th century, the Apalachicola tribe allied with the Spanish in Florida against the English in Carolina and were ultimately destroyed as a culture. The Yuchi tribe settled here later and constantly shifted their alliances with various European powers, until they were displaced by the expanding American frontier in the Southeast in the early 19th century.[46]

title: 1956 Grand Canyon TWA â€“ United Airlines Aviation Accident Site
desc: Crash area of first major (100+ deaths) commercial air disaster in the United States; led to creation of Federal Aviation Administration

title: Air Force Facility Missile Site 8(Titan II ICBM Site 571-7)
desc: Last surviving Titan II missile launch facility; inactive

title: Apache Pass and Fort Bowie
desc: Commemorates the conflict between the Chiricahua Apaches and the United States military; preserves the ruins of Fort Bowie

title: Awatovi Ruins
desc: Ruins of a 500 year old pueblo visited by Coronado's men in 1540

title: Casa Malpais Site
desc: Ruin built around 1250 A.D.; inhabited until about 1440 A.D

title: Mary Jane Colter buildings
desc: Includes Desert View Watchtower, Hermit's Rest, Hopi House, and The Lookout.

title: Desert Laboratory
desc: Founded in 1903 to study plant adaptation to an arid desert environment with long term experiments, this laboratory contributed significantly to the formation of Ecology as a science. Part of the University of Arizona

title: Double Adobe Site
desc: Archaeological site where development of the Cochise Culture occurred

title: El Tovar
desc: Classic lodge at South Rim of Grand Canyon

title: Fort Apache and Theodore Roosevelt School
desc: Site of historic Fort Apache; later converted to a school for the purpose of assimilating the native population. It is now a tribal museum.

title: Fort Huachuca
desc: Commemorates "Buffalo Soldiers"

title: Gatlin Site
desc: Preserves a Hohokam platform mound, pit houses, ball courts, middens, and prehistoric canals

title: Grand Canyon Depot
desc: Railway station constructed in 1909-10 for the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad

title: Grand Canyon Lodge
desc: Lodge at Bright Angel Point, on North Rim of Grand Canyon

title: Grand Canyon Park Operations Building
desc: National Park Service building; built in 1929; designed to blend with the natural surroundings

title: Grand Canyon Power House
desc: Rustic building designed to conceal the purpose of the building, which was to provide power to the railroad.

title: Grand Canyon Village
desc: Planned town significant for its urban planning and ecological sensitivity

title: Hoover Dam
desc: Historic dam, power plant and water-storage facility

title: Hubbell Trading Post
desc: Meeting ground of two cultures, the Navajo and the settlers

title: Jerome Historic District
desc: Copper mining town

title: Kinishba Ruins
desc: Large pueblo ruin; accessible via Fort Apache Historical Park.

title: Lehner Mammoth-Kill Site
desc: Clovis culture mammoth butchering site

desc: Ruins of Spanish mission church; founded 1691

desc: Observatory where Pluto was discovered

desc: Work site of C. Hart Merriam, path-breaking eco-biologist

title: Murray Springs Clovis Site
desc: Clovis culture site associated with bison and mammoth kills; site open to public.

title: Navajo Nation Council Chamber
desc: Center of government for Navajo Nation.

title: Old Oraibi

title: Painted Desert Inn
desc: Lodge in the Petrified Forest National Park

title: Phelps Dodge General Office Building
desc: Phelps Dodge mining company headquarters from 1896 to 1961

title: Point of Pines Sites
desc: Set of archaeological sites associated with Anasazi, Mogollon and Hohokam cultures

desc: Located at the former Poston War Relocation Center, this is the only surviving elementary school building from any World War II-era Japanese internment canp.

title: Pueblo Grande Ruin and Irrigation Sites
desc: Pueblo Grande Ruin and adjacent Hohokam-Pima Irrigation Sites

title: Sage Memorial Hospital School of Nursing
San Bernardino Ranch
desc: Historic cattle ranch

desc: Spanish mission, also known as Calabasas; part of Tumacacori National Historic Park.

title: San Xavier del Bac Mission
desc: Spanish mission founded in 1699

title: Sierra Bonita Ranch

title: Snaketown
desc: Archaeological remains of the Hohokam culture

title: Taliesin West
desc: Winter home of architect Frank Lloyd Wright

title: Tombstone Historic District
desc: Classic Western mining boomtown; location of the OK Corral

title: Tumacacori Museum
desc: Museum to Spanish missions that itself is an architectural landmark

title: Ventana Cave
desc: Archaeological site; has evidence of Native American occupation of the area for the last 4,000 years

title: Winona Site
desc: Archaeological site; evidence of cultural change following eruption of Sunset Crater

title: Yuma Crossing and Associated Sites
desc: Archaeological and historical sites including Yuma Quartermaster Depot and Arizona Territorial Prison
county: Yuma County, AZ and Imperial County, CA

title: Adak Army Base and Adak Naval Operating Base
desc: Established in 1942 as part of World War II, this military base was the launching pad for the American attack on the Japanese-held Aleutian Islands of Kiska and Attu.

title: Alaska Native Brotherhood Hall
desc: This 1914 meeting hall and headquarters building served the original chapter of Alaska Native Brotherhood, founded by Tlingits in the early 1900s to fight discrimination and represent interests of natives.

title: Amalik Bay Archeological District
desc: An archeological site located in Lake and Peninsula Borough

title: American Flag Raising Site
desc: In 1867, site of Russian flag lowering and American flag raising marking the transfer of Alaska to the U.S.; in 1959, after Alaska admitted as 49th state, site of first official raising of 49-star U.S. flag; also called Castle Hill.

title: Anangula Site
desc: Site of earliest signs of human occupation in the Aleutian Islands.

title: Attu Battlefield and U.S. Army and Navy Airfields on Attu
desc: Site of bloody battle in which only 29 of 2,500 Japanese survived, only battle on U.S. soil during World War II.

title: Bering Expedition Landing Site
desc: Site of first recorded contacts between natives and Europeans

title: Birnirk Site
desc: Sixteen prehistoric mounds of the Birnirk and Thule cultures.

title: Brooks River Archeological District
desc: An archaeological site located along an ancient beach and modern river. There are twenty separate well preserved sites which have provided a large number of Arctic Small Tool Tradition artifacts.

title: Cape Krusenstern Archeological District
desc: The archeological district comprises 114 ancient beach ridges which formed nearly 60 years apart. They provide a rare sequential look at over 5000 years of inhabitation.

title: Cape Nome Mining District Discovery Sites
desc: Significant for role in the history of gold mining in Alaska

title: Chaluka Site
desc: Includes a large mound; yields information about origins of Aleuts

title: Chilkoot Trail and Dyea Site
desc: Major access route from the coast to Yukon goldfields in the late 1890s.

title: Church of the Holy Ascension
desc: Built in 1826 by the Russian American Fur Company to help acclimate indigenous population in Russian Alaska.

title: Dry Creek Archeological Site
desc: This archeological site has provided evidence which supports the Bering land bridge theory

title: Dutch Harbor Naval Operating Base and Fort Mears, U.S. Army
desc: Only US fortifications in the Aleutian Islands prior to WWII, attacked by the Japanese Navy during the Battle of Dutch Harbor in June 1943.

title: Eagle Historic District
desc: Historic district with over 100 well-preserved buildings from the Gold Rush years on the Yukon River. Roald Amundsen announced his successful traverse of the Northwest Passage from here in 1905

title: Fort Durham Site
desc: One of three Hudson's Bay Company posts set up in Alaska

title: Fort Glenn
desc: Well preserved World War II defense base.

title: Fort William H. Seward
desc: Last of a series of 11 military posts established in Alaska during the gold rush era

title: Gallagher Flint Station Archeological Site
desc: Discovered in 1970 during the construction of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline, it was at the time the earliest dated archaeological site in northern Alaska.

title: Holy Assumption Orthodox Church
desc: Russian Orthodox church in Kenai, Alaska.

title: Ipiutak Site
desc: The type site for the Ipiutak culture

title: Iyatayet Site
desc: Shows evidence of several separate cultures, dating back as far as 6000 B.C.

title: Sheldon Jackson School
desc: Oldest institution of higher learning in Alaska

title: Kake Cannery
desc: Built 1912-1940; significant for role in history of salmon canning in Alaska

title: Kennecott Mines
desc: Site of discovery of copper in 1900 and subsequent mining activities

title: Kijik Archeological District
desc: Related to the history of the Dena'ina Athabaskan Indians

title: Japanese Occupation Site, Kiska Island
desc: Site of the Japanese occupation of Kiska which along with nearby Attu were the only US land occupied by the Japanese during World War II

title: Kodiak Naval Operating Base and Forts Greely and Abercrombie
desc: World War II-related facilities

title: Ladd Field
desc: Primary role during WWII was major stopping point for the Lend-Lease program.

title: Leffingwell Camp Site
desc: Campsite of geologist and polar explorer Ernest de Koven Leffingwell on Arctic coast of Alaska, not far from Prudhoe Bay.

title: Nenana (river steamboat)
desc: River steamboat; only surviving wooden one of this type.

title: New Russia Site
desc: Site of Russian trading post attacked and destroyed by Tlingit natives.

title: Old Sitka
desc: Also known as the Redoubt St. Archangel Michael Site, this was the site of a Russian-American Company settlement, established in 1799 and destroyed by Tlingit attack in 1802.

title: Onion Portage Archeological District
desc: Perhaps most important archaeological site in Alaska; caribou river crossing; human presence for millennia.

title: Palugvik Site
desc: Includes a large midden yielding information about Eskimo culture in the area.

title: Russian-American Building #29
desc: Siding covered log building; dates back to the years after the 1867 purchase of Alaska.

title: Russian-American Magazin
desc: Storehouse building associated with the Russian and then the American trading companies active in Alaska.

title: Russian Bishop's House
desc: One of four surviving examples of Russian Colonial Style architecture in the Western Hemisphere.

title: St. Michael's Cathedral
desc: Primary evidence of Russian influence in North America.

title: Seal Island Historic District
desc: Historic buildings related to Northern Fur Seal hunting in the Pribilof Islands and its restriction in 1911 and 1966.

title: Sitka Naval Operating Base and U.S. Army Coastal Defenses
desc: Commissioned as Sitka Naval Air Station in October 1939, it was redesignated the Naval Operating Base, July 1942. Protected the North Pacific during World War II.[6]

title: Sitka Spruce Plantation
desc: First recorded afforestation project in North America; Russian settlers began in 1805; attempt to make Unalaska self-sufficient in timber.

title: Skagway Historic District and White Pass
desc: Historic frontier Gold Rush town and trail leading to White Pass on the border of Canada. Over 100 buildings from the era survive, though they are threatened by continued development. Mentioned in The Call of the Wild by Jack London.

title: George C. Thomas Memorial Library
desc: The public library for Fairbanks from its construction in 1909 until the opening of the Noel Wien Public Library in 1977. Site of 1915 meeting between U.S. officials and native Alaskans to settle land claims.

title: Three Saints Bay Site
desc: Site of the first Russian settlement in Alaska in 1784.

title: Wales Site
desc: Site of first discovery of how the Thule culture followed the Birnirk culture in precontact whaling populations of the Alaskan shoreline.

title: Yukon Island Main Site
desc: Related to the Kachemak Bay Culture.

title: Arkansas Post
desc: Commemorates the first semi-permanent European settlement in the Lower Mississippi Valley (1686); an American Revolutionary War skirmish (1783); the first territorial capital of Arkansas (1819â€“1821); and the American Civil War Battle of Fort Hindman (1863)

title: Daisy Bates House
desc: Supporting site for desegregation of Little Rock Central High School

title: Bathhouse Row
desc: In Hot Springs National Park; largest collection of bathhouses in the United States; remains of the only federally-run spa

title: Beginning Point of the Louisiana Purchase Survey
desc: Point from which the lands acquired through the Louisiana Purchase of 1803 were subsequently surveyed[3]

desc: Where Elias Camp Morris preached, unofficial headquarters for National Baptist Convention

title: Eaker Site
desc: Archaeological site; shows evidence of pre-historic Nodena populations and also Quapaw occupation

title: Fort Smith
desc: This site includes the remains of two 19th-century U.S. military forts and the Federal Court for the Western District of Arkansas.

title: Little Rock Central High School
desc: Focal point of the Little Rock Integration Crisis of 1957

title: Menard-Hodges Site
desc: Site includes two large mounds and several house mounds, as well as remains of a 17th-century French trading post; now owned by the National Park Service and administered as part of the Arkansas Post National Memorial.

title: Nodena Site
desc: Located on Nodena Plantation; type site for an important Late Mississippian cultural component, the Nodena phase; date from about 1400-1700 AD; first excavations in 1897.

title: Old State House
desc: Oldest surviving state capitol building west of the Mississippi River.

title: Parkin Indian Mound
desc: A Late Mississippian and protohistoric palisaded village with one mound; may be the town of Casqui mentioned by 16th century Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto.

title: Joseph Taylor Robinson House
desc: Home of influential Arkansas governor and U.S. senator

title: Rohwer Relocation Center Memorial Cemetery
desc: Site of a World War II Japanese American internment camp

title: Toltec Mounds Site
desc: One of the most significant remnants of Native American life in the state.

title: The Abbey, Joaquin Miller House
desc: Joaquin Miller, known as the "Poet of the Sierras", lived here from 1886 until his death in 1913.

title: The Ahwahnee
desc: National Park Service-built and operated hotel in Yosemite National Park; designed by Gilbert Stanley Underwood; exemplifies National Park Service Rustic architecture.

title: Alcatraz Island
desc: Former maximum security Federal prison; Frank Morris escaped, but few others did; part of Golden Gate National Recreation Area; visited by tourist ferries.

title: Alma (scow schooner)
desc: Flat-bottomed scow schooner that was built in 1891 and used in San Francisco Bay and Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta. Now part of the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Angelus Temple
desc: Church built by and for Aimee Semple McPherson, evangelical sensation of the 1920s and 1930s.

title: Juan de Anza House
desc: One-story adobe house typical of Mexican era, later "Americanized", also in typical way.

title: Aquatic Park Historic District
desc: Streamline Moderne beach, pier, and public bathhouse built by the WPA in 1936. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Asilomar Conference Grounds
desc: Arts and Crafts style conference center built for the YWCA by Julia Morgan in 1913.

title: Balboa Park
desc: 1,200 acre (4.9 kmÂ²) urban cultural complex in San Diego. Reserved in 1855, it is one of the oldest public recreation sites in the US. It includes open areas and vegetation as well as museums, theaters, gardens, shops, restaurants and the San Diego Zoo.

title: Balclutha (square-rigger)
desc: The only remaining square rigged ship in the San Francisco Bay area, it was built in 1886 and served on several different trade routes. It is now part of the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Baldwin Hills Village
desc: Now known as Village Green, this 627 unit condo complex was one of the first new planned communities when it was built between 1935 and 1942.

title: Hubert H. Bancroft Ranch House
desc: Adobe home of historian and ethnologist Hubert Howe Bancroft, publisher of many Pacific Coast histories and books on Native American culture.

title: Bank of Italy Building
desc: Became the headquarters of Bank of Italy in 1908 (precursor of the Bank of America); also known as the Clay-Montgomery Building.

title: Aline Barnsdall Complex (Hollyhock House)
desc: Hollyhock House, a building designed by Frank Lloyd Wright and built in 1919â€“1921 for Aline Barnsdall. Now the centerpiece of the Barnsdall Art Park.

title: Berkeley (ferry)
desc: First propeller-driven ferry on the west coast; currently the main "building" of the Maritime Museum of San Diego.

title: Big Four House
desc: Built in 1852; house where Collis Huntington, Mark Hopkins, Leland Stanford, and Charles Crocker organized the Central Pacific railway and founded the Southern Pacific Railroad.

title: Bodie Historic District
desc: Establish in 1859, it became a Gold Rush boomtown in 1876. It is currently a State park preserved in arrested decay, neither restored nor destroyed. It is one of very few towns of this type to survive untouched.

title: Borax Lake Site
desc: The archaeological type site of the unique Paleo-Indian Clovis people known as the Post Pattern. This site extended their known range and introduced an unusual lake shore dwelling population.

title: Bradbury Building
desc: 1893 Italian Renaissance architectural landmark. Known for its striking interiors and cage elevators. It has been used extensively as a location in films such as Blade Runner.

title: Luther Burbank House and Garden
desc: City park containing the former home, greenhouse, gardens, and grave of noted American horticulturist Luther Burbank.

title: C.A. Thayer (schooner)
desc: Schooner built in 1895; now preserved at the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park; worked in lumber trade to San Francisco from Washington, Oregon, and Northern California. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Carmel Mission
desc: The second Roman Catholic California Mission Church, this was the headquarters of the padre presidente, Father Fermin Francisco de Lasuen. It was destroyed in the mid-19th century and restored in 1884 and 1920. It remains a parish church today.

title: Carrizo Plain Archeological District
desc: Historically important and environmentally sensitive grassland area.

title: Jose Castro House
desc: Historic adobe home built by JosÃ© Castro, Commandant General of Northern California. It is part of the San Juan Bautista Historic District.

title: Coloma
desc: Town where the California Gold Rush when James W. Marshall discovered gold at Sutter's mill on January 24, 1848. Now a ghost town, it is a significant part of the Marshall Gold Discovery State Historic Park

title: Columbia Historic District
desc: Within two years of discovering gold in this town, it was the 3rd largest city in California. The historic district is now an open museum and the best preserved California Gold Rush town.

title: Commander's House, Fort Ross
desc: Only original structure at Fort Ross; also known as Rotchev House; Russian-built in 1812

title: Coso Rock Art District(formerly Big and Little Petroglyph Canyons)

title: Donner Camp Sites

title: Drakes Bay Historic and Archeological District
desc: The recognized landing site of Francis Drake in 1579 and Sebastian Rodriguez CermeÃ±o in 1595, and the early interactions between Native Americans and these European visitors.

title: Eames House (Case Study House #8)
desc: Built in 1949 by husband-and-wife design pioneers Charles and Ray Eames; also known as Case Study House No. 8.

title: Elmshaven (Ellen White House)
desc: Ellen Gould White lived and worked here from 1900 until her death in 1915. She was notable for her prophetic ministry which led to the rise of the Seventh-day Adventist Church.

title: Estudillo House
desc: Adobe house; constructed in 1827; was considered one of the finest houses in Mexican California.

title: Eureka (double-ended ferry)
desc: Side-wheel paddle steamboat; built in 1890 by the San Francisco and North Pacific Railroad Company; preserved at the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: USCGC Fir
desc: 174 foot U.S. Coast Guard cutter; lighthouse tender; decommissioned.

title: First Church of Christ, Scientist
desc: Church designed by Bernard Ralph Maybeck

title: James C. Flood Mansion
desc: Mansion of James C. Flood, 19th century silver-baron; first brownstone building built west of the Mississippi River; one of the only buildings on Nob Hill to survive the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and fire; purchased by the Pacific-Union Club after the earthquake

title: Folsom Powerhouse
desc: Built in late 19th century using prison labor from Folsom Prison; first delivered power to Sacramento in 1895; remained in operation until 1952.

title: Fort Ross
desc: Established by Ivan Kuskov of the Russian-American Company in 1812; thriving settlement from 1812 to 1841

title: Fresno Sanitary Landfill
desc: Opened in 1937; first modern landfill in the U.S.; model for other landfills around the country; and one of the longest-lived.

title: David B. Gamble House
desc: Arts and Crafts masterpiece; shows influence from traditional Japanese aesthetics and a certain California spaciousness born of available land and a permissive climate.

title: GonzÃ¡lez House
desc: Built about 1825 by Don Rafael Gonzales; typical of Mexican-era adobe town houses; adobe walls at least 2' thick

title: Guajome Ranch House
desc: Spanish Colonial hacienda with two courtyards.

title: Hale Solar Observatory
desc: Laboratory of George Ellery Hale, inventor of the spectroheliograph, with which he made his discoveries of the solar vortices and magnetic fields of sun spots.

title: Hanna-Honeycomb House
desc: Located on Stanford University campus, this was Frank Lloyd Wright's first work in the San Francisco region as well as his first work with non-rectangular structures.

title: Harada House
desc: Property involved in 1916â€“1918 constitutional test of an alien land law; at issue was the rights of the children of a Japanese immigrant

title: Hearst San Simeon Estate
desc: Built by newspaper magnate William Randolph Hearst; open for public tours; Hearst formally named the estate "La Cuesta Encantada".

title: Hercules (tug)
desc: This 1907 steam tug is now a museum ship at the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Lou Henry and Herbert Hoover House
desc: Designed by Lou Henry Hoover, wife of Herbert Hoover, this is where the Hoovers lived before and after his presidency. It is now the official residence of the president of Stanford University

title: USS Hornet (CVS-12) (aircraft carrier)
desc: Essex class aircraft carrier which was commissioned in November 1943. She played a role in the Pacific battles of World War II and then went on to serve in the Vietnam War. It also recovered the Apollo Astronauts as they returned from the Moon.

title: Hotel del Coronado
desc: The largest beach resort on the North American Pacific Coast, this Victorian building is an iconic symbol of San Diego.

title: Edwin Hubble House
desc: Home of astronomer Edwin Hubble from 1925 until his death in 1953.

title: Jeremiah O'Brien (Liberty ship)
desc: This Liberty ship is a rare survivor of the 6,939-ship armada that stormed Normandy on D-Day, 1944.

title: Knight's Ferry Bridge
desc: Historic bridge

title: La Purisima Mission
desc: Now a historical park, it is the only example in California of a "complete" mission complex.

title: Lake Merritt Wild Duck Refuge
desc: Now known as Lake Merritt park, it is notable for being the first official wildlife refuge in the United States, designated in 1870.

title: Lane Victory (victory ship)
desc: A rare example of a Victory Ship, it is now a still operational museum ship which makes 6 public cruises a year to Catalina Island.

title: Larkin House
desc: This house, part of the larger landmark district Monterey State Historic Park, combined Spanish building techniques with New England features, creating the Monterey Colonial style of architecture.

title: Las Flores Adobe
desc: An estancia halfway between two missions, it is now part of a Boy Scout camp located inside Camp Pendleton just off of Interstate 5.

title: Leconte Memorial Lodge
desc: Built by the Sierra Club in 1903 in honor of Joseph LeConte, one of the founding members of the Sierra Club. It was a Yosemite visitors center, but is now run by the Sierra Club as a museum and library.

title: Lightship WAL-605, Relief
desc: A lightvessel now located in Oakland

title: Little Tokyo Historic District
desc: An ethnic Japanese American district in downtown Los Angeles, one of three official Japantowns in the United States.

title: Locke Historic District
desc: The largest remaining example of a historic rural Chinese American community, built in 1915.

title: Jack London Ranch
desc: Home of Jack London from 1905 until his death.

title: Los Alamos Ranch House
desc: A good example of the Mexican style single story adobe ranch-house located next to the El Camino Real. It was often used as an overnight stop when travelling between Santa Barbara and Monterey.

title: Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum
desc: The only stadium in the world which has hosted the Summer Olympic Games (1932 /1984), the World Series (1959) and the Super Bowl (1967 /1973). It is currently the home of the USC Trojans football team.

title: Los Cerritos Ranch House
desc: Largest adobe home built in Southern California during Mexican era.

title: Lower Klamath National Wildlife Refuge
desc: This national wildlife refuge, established in 1908, was the first large block of public land set aside for wildlife management purposes. Because of the refuge's extensive overlap with the Klamath Basin water reclamation project, it has become an ongoing example of the tensions between conservation and economic demands in public land management.

title: Manzanar War Relocation Center
desc: The most widely known American forced relocation camp where 11,070 Japanese Americans were imprisoned during World War II.

title: Mare Island Naval Shipyard
desc: The first US naval facility on the West Coast, it built and supported WWII naval forces as well as nuclear submarines. It closed in 1996 and is currently under redevelopment which is threatening the historic buildings.

title: Marin County Civic Center
desc: The last major commission by Frank Lloyd Wright, this government run complex hosts a variety of events including the county fair. Its architecture has led to inclusion in or inspiration for several films. It is also known for two violent attacks in the 1970s.

title: Mendocino Woodlands Recreational Demonstration Area
desc: The only Recreational Demonstration Area built by the Civilian Conservation Corps that's been continually used as a campground. It has been managed by a nonprofit agency since 1949 and remains in use today as Mendocino Woodlands State Park.

title: Mission Beach Roller Coaster
desc: One of only 2 remaining wooden coasters on the West coast, it was built in 1925 by noted coaster builders Prior and Church. It was saved from destruction in 1987, restored, and is still operating today.

title: Mission Inn
desc: This hotel has become the largest Mission Revival style through progressive additions and embellishments since its first predecessor cottage was built in 1876. In addition to lodgings, it features shops, a chapel, furniture from around the world, and Tiffany windows.

title: Mission San Miguel ArcÃ¡ngel
desc: The 16th California Mission church remains well preserved and still in use today though under earthquake remediation construction. Inside are murals by Esteban Munras.

title: Mission Santa InÃ©s
desc: The 19th California Mission church was the site of an Indian revolt in 1824. It has undergone restoration since the 1940s and is a working parish church today.

title: Modjeska House
desc: Designed by Stanford White, from 1888 to 1906 this was the home of Helena Modjeska, a Polish patriot and Shakespearean actress.

title: Monterey Old Town Historic District
desc: Also known as Monterey State Historic Park, this NHLD contains both California's First Theatre, and the Monterey Customs House, where the American flag was first raised over California. It also incorporates the National Historic Landmarked Larkin House known for its leading architecture.

title: John Muir House
desc: John Muir lived here from 1890 until his death in 1914, the time period of some of his most notable achievements including founding the Sierra Club and laying the groundwork for the creation of the National Park Service. It is open to the public.

title: New Almaden
desc: Also known as Senador, one of the oldest and most productive mercury mines in the United States. It helped ensure the California Gold Rush could take place. Now part of Almaden Quicksilver County Park.

title: Richard M. Nixon Birthplace
desc: The birthplace and home of President Richard Milhous Nixon from 1913 to 1922. Now part of the Richard Nixon Presidential Library and Museum

title: Frank Norris Cabin
desc: Also known as Redwood Retreat this was the home of author Frank Norris in the last year of his life.

title: Nuestra Senora Reina de la Paz
desc: Headquarters of the National Farm Workers Federation, now the Cesar Chavez National Monument. Includes the gravesite of co-founder CÃ©sar ChÃ¡vez

title: Oak Grove Butterfield Stage Station
desc: The only surviving station house on the Butterfield Overland Mail stagecoach line. The nearby location of Warner's Ranch was also part of the line.

title: Old Customhouse
desc: This 1827 Adobe structure is the oldest public building in California and is where the American Flag was raised, declaring California part of the United States. It is now a museum located inside the Monterey State Historic Park, itself a NHLD.

title: Old Mission Dam
desc: The first major irrigation project on the Pacific coast, this dam supplied water for milling and irrigation at the Mission San Diego de AlcalÃ¡, 5 miles away. Now part of Mission Trails Regional Park

title: Old Sacramento Historic District
desc: Built up after the California Gold Rush, this historic district also includes the NHL locations of the Pony Express Terminal and the Big Four House.

title: Old Scripps Building
desc: The first building of Scripps Institution of Oceanography, which is the oldest oceanographic institute in the United States. It formed the starting point of what has become the University of California, San Diego.

title: Old United States Mint
desc: Built for the San Francisco Mint in 1874 to handle the overflow from the California Gold Rush, this building is affectionately as The Granite Lady. It is one of the few that survivors of the great 1906 San Francisco earthquake and served until 1937.

title: USS Pampanito (submarine)
desc: A Balao class submarine, she served in World War II before becoming a museum ship and part of the San Francisco Maritime National Park Association. She still has several working parts, including the periscopes and a torpedo tube.

title: Paramount Theatre
desc: The largest theatre on the West Coast when it was built, it is notable for its Art Deco appearance. It is the home of the Oakland East Bay Symphony and the Oakland Ballet and is managed by a nonprofit organization.

title: Parsons Memorial Lodge
desc: This solidly built structure was the first stone structure in a National Park. It was built by the Sierra Club and is still standing today with only minor variations. It reflects the Bay Area architecture influences of Bernard Maybeck as well as the practical weather concerns of the High Sierra valley.

title: Petaluma Adobe
desc: The largest example of Monterey Colonial architecture in the United States, this adobe structure was the ranch house of General Mariano Guadalupe Vallejo, commandant of the Sonoma Pueblo. It is now the centerpiece of Petaluma Adobe State Historic Park, which is threatened with closure.

title: Pioneer Deep Space Station
desc: NASA's Deep Space Network for tracking unmanned spacecraft in deep space was inaugurated when this antenna became operational in 1958.

title: Point Reyes Lifeboat Station
desc: Last remaining instance of a USLS rail launched lifeboat station, commonly used on the Pacific coast. This site rescued crews from ships that foundered on Point Reyes. It is now protected as part of the Point Reyes National Seashore.

title: Pony Express Terminal
desc: The Western end of the Pony Express, this bank building has also served as the first home of the Supreme Court of California. It is now part of the Old Sacramento State Historic Park, itself a National Historic Landmark District.

title: Potomac (Presidential yacht)
desc: Formerly the USCGC Electra, this ship was Franklin Delano Rooseveltâ€™s presidential yacht from 1936 until his death in 1945 and only one of three still existing presidential yachts. On August 3, 1941, she played a decoy role while Roosevelt snuck off to sign the Atlantic Charter. She is now a museum ship.

title: Presidio of San Francisco
desc: Used as a fortified military base from 1776 to 1995 by Spain, Mexico, and the United States. It is now part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area and serves a mix of commercial and public uses. It is required to be financially self-supporting by 2013.

title: Ralph J. Scott (fireboat)
desc: A fireboat for the LAFD from 1925 until its retirement in 2003, it could pump 17,000 US gal/min (1,070 L/s). It is now located near the Los Angeles Maritime Museum.

title: William C. Ralston Home
desc: Home of William Chapman Ralston, a San Francisco businessman, founder of the Bank of California, and financier of the Comstock Lode. Now part of Notre Dame de Namur University.

title: Rancho Camulos
desc: The home of Ygnacio del Valle, an alcalde of Los Angeles and member of the California State Assembly. The ranch was known as the Home of Ramona because it is likely that the popular 1884 novel Ramona by Helen Hunt Jackson was set there. The novel helped in raising awareness about the Californio lifestyle. It is now a museum.

title: Rangers' Club
desc: Stephen Tyng Mather, the wealthy first director of the National Park Service personally donated this building to house the newly hired rangers covering Yosemite National Park. Its rustic architecture inspired all National Park construction through WWII.

title: Rogers Dry Lake
desc: Centerpiece of Edwards Air Force Base, this endorheic desert salt pan in the Mojave Desert has the worlds largest Compass Rose and the worlds largest runway at 7.2 miles. It is one of the alternate Space Shuttle landing sites.

title: Room 307, Gilman Hall, University of California
desc: Room 307 in Gilman Hall at UCB is where Glenn T. Seaborg and his coworkers identified plutonium as a new element on February 23, 1941.

title: Rose Bowl
desc: Home field of the UCLA Bruins college football team as well as the annual Rose Bowl Game. It also hosted events from the 1932 and 1984 Summer Olympics

title: Royal Presidio Chapel
desc: This cathedral is the oldest continuously operating parish, the oldest stone building in California, the smallest cathedral in the United States and one of the two oldest cathedrals in the United States. It is the only existing Presidio cathedral in California and the only original building in the Monterey Presidio.

title: San Diego Mission Church
desc: This was the first Spanish Mission in Alta California and the start of El Camino Real. Originally located in the Presidio of San Diego, it later moved a few miles away. The nearby Old Mission Dam, also a NHL, provided water for milling and farming.

title: San Diego Presidio
desc: The first fortified presidio, it along with the first mission, San Diego Mission Church, paved the way for Spanish colonization of California. No structures remain, but the site is now located in Presidio Park.

title: San Francisco Bay Discovery Site
desc: On November 4, 1769 the expedition of Spanish explorer Gaspar de PortolÃ  reached the summit of the 1,200-foot (370 m) high Sweeney Ridge, where he sighted San Francisco Bay. It is now part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area.

title: San Francisco Cable Cars
desc: An iconic image of San Francisco, this is the only remaining permanently operational manually operated cable car system in the world.

title: San Francisco Civic Center
desc: The United Nations Charter was signed here in 1945 as well as the post WWII peace treaty with Japan. This collection of Beaux Arts buildings serves a number of uses, including the Exposition Auditorium from the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition.

title: San Francisco Port of Embarkation, U.S. Army
desc: Originally built during the American Civil War for coastal defense, this fort became the primary transportation hub in the Pacific for the United States during World War I and World War II. In World War II alone, over 1,647,174 passengers and 23,589,472 tons went through this fort. It is now part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area

title: San Juan Bautista Plaza Historic District
desc: A prime example of the Spanish-Mexican colonial plan of buildings surrounding the central plaza and Mission church. The NHLD also includes the Jose Castro House, itself a National Historic Landmark. It was featured prominently in the Hitchcock film Vertigo.

title: San Luis Rey Mission Church
desc: California's most pristine Spanish Mission Complex, this is the third church at this site.

title: Santa Barbara County Courthouse
desc: Known for the beauty of its Spanish-Colonial Revival architecture, which inspired and influenced many other designers.

title: Santa Barbara Mission
desc: The only Spanish mission in California to remain under the leadership of the Franciscan Friars since the day of its founding.

title: Santa Cruz Looff Carousel and Roller Coaster
desc: The Looff family was one of the major early manufacturers of carousels, including this 1911 example. Only five other intact Looff carousels remain in the United States. The 1924 Giant Dipper roller coaster is the older of the two large, wooden scaffolded roller coasters remaining on the West Coast.

title: Santa Monica Looff Hippodrome
desc: Built by the Looff family to house one of their carousels, this structure now houses a different carousel, but remains a rare example of what was once a much larger amusement complex.

title: Upton Sinclair House
desc: Home of American novelist Upton Sinclair between 1942 and 1966 and where he wrote most of his later works.

title: Sonoma Plaza
desc: The largest plaza in California, this was the location of the Bear Flag Revolt in 1846 which led to the Mexican-American War

title: Space Flight Operations Facility
desc: Control room at Jet Propulsion Laboratory where all NASA interplanetary and deep space missions are monitored.

title: Space Launch Complex 10
desc: First built in 1958 to test missiles, it was used to launch space missions from 1963 to 1980. It is now a rare, well preserved example of the equipment and facilities from that era.

title: Leland Stanford House
desc: The home of Leland Stanford, Governor of California from 1862 to 1863, U.S. Senator from 1885 to 1893, railroad tycoon, member of the Big Four and founder of Stanford University.

title: Star of India (bark)
desc: A seaworthy iron hulled museum ship in the San Diego Maritime Museum, she is the oldest ship that still sails regularly and the oldest iron hulled merchant ship still floating.

title: Steedman Estate(Casa del Herrero)
desc: Designed by architect George Washington Smith, this 1920s, 11-acre estate is considered one of the finest examples of Spanish Colonial Revival architecture in the United States.

title: Sutter's Fort
desc: A 19th century agricultural and trade colony, it was known for its connection to the Donner Party, the California Gold Rush, and the formation of Sacramento as well as its proximity to the California Trail and Siskiyou Trails. Now a state park, threatened with closure in 2008.

title: Swedenborgian Church
desc: One of California's earliest pure Arts and Crafts buildings, this Swedenborgianism church remains open today with almost no architectural changes.

title: Tao House
desc: America's only Nobel Prize-winning playwright Eugene O'Neill lived here from 1937 to 1944 while writing his final and most memorable plays: The Iceman Cometh, Long Day's Journey Into Night, and A Moon for the Misbegotten.

title: The Forty Acres
desc: Served as the original headquarters of the United Farm Workers, the first permanent agricultural labor union in the United States.

title: Tolowot, Gunther Island Site 67
desc: An archaeological site surrounding a Wiyot shell midden, located in Tolowot, on Indian Island in Humboldt Bay near Eureka, California. This site helped define the Gunther Pattern in archaeology and was also the site of the 1860 Wiyot Massacre.

title: Tule Lake Segregation Center
desc: The largest Japanese American internment camp, it also had the highest security and stayed open longest, even after World War II. The Redress movement in the 1980s and pilgrimages to Tule Lake led to the Civil Liberties Act of 1988.

title: Twenty-Five-Foot Space Simulator
desc: An 85 foot high stainless-steel cylinder at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory used for testing spacecraft in space-like conditions. Ranger, Surveyor, Mariner, and Voyager spacecraft were all tested in this facility.

title: Unitary Plan Wind Tunnel
desc: This wind tunnel built in the 1950s allowed commercial and military aircraft as well as the Space Shuttle to be aerodynamically tested.

title: United States Immigration Station, Angel Island
desc: The "Ellis Island of the West" processed over 1 million Asian immigrants between 1910 and 1940. Now part of Angel Island State Park, it was renovated in 2009.

title: United States Post Office and Court House (James R. Browning U.S. Court of Appeals)
desc: Court House

title: Walker Pass
desc: Joseph Reddeford Walker mapped this pass in 1834 after learning of it from Native Americans. He then led the first immigrant wagon train through it in 1846. This pass significantly contributed to the development of California.

title: Wapama (steam schooner)
desc: This 204' wooden schooner was one of 200 ships plying the lumber trade along the Pacific coast. Now managed by the San Francisco Maritime National Historic Park, she has been moved to Richmond, California for possible renovation. She is threatened by severe dry rot. Official plaque located in the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park Visitor Center, located at the corner of Hyde and Jefferson Streets.

title: Warner's Ranch
desc: The only trading post between New Mexico and Los Angeles, this ranch developed into a stop on the Butterfield Overland Mail stagecoach line along with nearby Oak Grove. Now a hot springs resort.

title: Watts Towers
desc: These towers built by Simon Rodia are a superb example of non-traditional vernacular architecture and American NaÃ¯ve art.

title: Wawona Hotel and Thomas Hill Studio
desc: Built in 1879 for tourists visiting the Mariposa Grove, this hotel is also where the Hudson River School painter Thomas Hill painted towards the end of his life.

title: Well No. 4, Pico Canyon Oil Field
desc: Drilled in 1876 to 376 feet (115 m), this was the first commercially successful oil well in California, producing 25 barrels a day (4 mÂ³/d).

title: Yuma Crossing and Associated Sites
desc: A major crossroads for Alta California as well as the Westward expansion of the United States. It has several archaeological and historical sites, shared with Arizona across the Colorado River, including Fort Yuma and other state parks.

title: Aspendale
desc: House and small plantation, intact from 1771.

title: Jacob Broom House
desc: Home of constitutional convention delegate Jacob Broom, this historic house is near Brandywine Creek. It is part of the Hagley Museum.

title: Corbit-Sharp House
desc: House built in 1772 exemplifying influence of late Georgian architecture from Philadelphia into surrounding regions.

title: John Dickinson House
desc: Delaware home where John Dickinson wrote Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania analyzing economic difficulties of colonial America, before the American Revolutionary War

title: Eleutherian Mills
desc: Gunpowder mills along Brandywine Creek founded by EleuthÃ¨re IrÃ©nÃ©e du Pont in 1802. It is part of the Hagley Museum.

title: Fort Christina
desc: This was the first and principal settlement of the New Sweden colony.

title: Holy Trinity (Old Swedes) Church
desc: The oldest surviving church from New Sweden, it hosted services in Swedish from 1698 well into the 1800s.

title: Howard High School
desc: An all African American high school, this school was subject of Gebhart v. Belton, a desegregation case that was combined with others in the landmark Brown vs. Board of Education decision by the United States Supreme Court.

title: Lightship LV-118 (Overfalls)
desc: Unique lightship was one of few to remain in service during World War II

title: Lombardy Hall
desc: Home of Gunning Bedford, Jr., a delegate to constitutional convention and signer of the U.S. Constitution.

title: New Castle Court House
desc: Hosted Delaware's colonial assembly from 1704-1777.

title: New Castle Historic District
desc: Capital of Delaware colony from 1651 to 1761, having well preserved architecture.

title: Stonum
desc: Home of George Read, signer of the Declaration of Independence

title: Bent's Old Fort
desc: Adobe fort built in 1833 to trade with Plains Indians and trappers, on Santa Fe Trail

title: Central City/Black Hawk Historic District
desc: Former gold mining camps in the Front Range of the Rocky Mountains, once known as the 'Richest Square Mile on Earth

title: Colorado Chautauqua
desc: This 1898 Chautauqua is the only one West of the Mississippi, one of only four continuously operating since its inception, and the only one open year round.

title: Cripple Creek Historic District
desc: The gold mining town of Cripple Creek and the surrounding hills

title: Denver & Rio Grande Railroad San Juan Extension(Cumbres & Toltec Scenic Railroad)
desc: Longest & most complete representation of late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century railroading.
county: Archuleta, CO, Conejos, CO, and Rio Arriba, NM

title: Denver Civic Center
desc: City Beautiful-era civic center.

title: Durango-Silverton Narrow-Gauge Railroad
desc: Narrow gauge mining railroad which has continued to serve as a tourist line between Durango and Silverton

title: Georgetown-Silver Plume Historic District
desc: Historic district which includes the silver mining towns of Georgetown and Silver Plume as well as the 1884 railway engineering marvel which connects them, the Georgetown Loop Railroad.

title: Granada Relocation Center
desc: World War II Japanese American internment center

title: Leadville Historic District
desc: Historic Leadville, Colorado mining district and village area

title: Lindenmeier Site
desc: The only extensive Folsom culture campsite yet found with artifacts dating from approximately 11200 BCE to 3000 BCE.

title: Lowry Ruin
desc: Ancient Pueblo Peoples archaeological site from 1060 with a very large kiva

title: Ludlow Tent Colony Site
desc: Site of 1914 miners' strike that culminated in Ludlow Massacre

title: Mesa Verde Administrative District
desc: First buildings built by the National Park Service with intent to reflect cultural traditions in the park area, built in 1921

title: Philadelphia Toboggan Company Carousel No. 6
desc: Carousel built for Elitch Gardens in 1905. In 1928 it moved to Kit Carson County fairgrounds where it remains open today. It is the only antique carousel in America retaining its original paint on both the scenery panels and the animals, and it is the only surviving Philadelphia Toboggan Company menagerie carousel.

title: Pikes Peak
desc: Pike's Peak (everything above 14,000 feet (4,300Â m) elevation). This mountain was inspiration for "America the Beautiful" as well as the motto "Pike's Peak or Bust"

title: Pike's Stockade
desc: Explorer Zebulon Pike set up a fort here.

title: Raton Pass
desc: Mountain pass between New Mexico and Colorado
county: Las Animas, CO and Colfax, NM

title: Rocky Mountain National Park Administration Building
desc: Also known as the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center, it was designed by Taliesin Associated Architects, their first major work after Frank Lloyd Wright had died. It demonstrated modern architecture could be successful inside the National Parks and was the last significant project in Mission 66.

title: Shenandoah-Dives (Mayflower) Mill
desc: Only surviving example of a selective flotation mill in Colorado.

title: Silverton Historic District
desc: Former silver mining town, home of the Shenandoah-Dives (Mayflower) Mill and one end of the Durango-Silverton Narrow-Gauge Railroad

title: Telluride Historic District
desc: Former gold mining boomtown, it is now an artistic retreat and a ski resort town

title: Trujillo Homestead
desc: Early ranch settlement (1880s) in the San Luis Valley, with a surviving period ranch house; located on a Nature Conservancy property near Great Sand Dunes National Park.

title: United States Air Force Academy, Cadet Area
desc: Bold use of Modern architecture at the United States Air Force Academy, especially with the Cadet Chapel

title: Richard Alsop IV House
desc: This distinctive house was built in the late 1830s in a transitional Greek-Italianate style. It now belongs to Wesleyan University.

title: A. Everett Austin, Jr., House
desc: Social hotspot and home of innovative Wadsworth Atheneum director Arthur Everett Austin, Jr..

title: Henry Barnard House
desc: Home of educator instrumental in the development of the American public school system.

title: Birdcraft Sanctuary
desc: Oldest bird sanctuary in the U.S., where Mabel Osgood Wright originated "birdscaping".

title: Henry C. Bowen House (Roseland)
desc: Gothic revival summer cottage visited by three U.S. presidents.

title: Bush-Holley House
desc: Home of Cos Cob Art Colony, c.1890-1920.

title: Buttolph-Williams House
desc: Exemplifies traditional early New England design.

title: Charles W. Morgan (Bark)
desc: Only surviving wooden ship from the nineteenth-century American whaling fleet.

title: Cheney Brothers Historic District
desc: A nineteenth century silk mill and traditional company town.

title: Russell Henry Chittenden House
desc: Home of Russell Henry Chittenden, the "father of American biochemistry".

title: Coltsville Historic District
desc: Original designated solely to encompass Armsmear, the home of arms maker Samuel Colt, this historic district was expanded in 1988 to include the Colt Armory, as well as worker housing and Colt Park.

title: Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station
desc: Home of the first state agricultural experiment station

title: Connecticut Hall, Yale University
desc: Oldest building at Yale University

title: Connecticut State Capitol
desc: Designed by Richard Upjohn in Gothic and French Renaissance styles topped by gold leaf dome

title: Prudence Crandall House
desc: Home of the abolitionist and educator Prudence Crandall

title: James Dwight Dana House
desc: Home of Yale geologist James Dwight Dana, designed by Henry Austin.

title: Silas Deane House
desc: Home of Silas Deane, member of the Continental Congress and America's first diplomat

title: Oliver Ellsworth Homestead
desc: Home of Oliver Ellsworth, the second Chief Justice of the United States.

title: Emma C. Berry
desc: One of the oldest surviving commercial vessels in the United States.

title: First Church Of Christ
desc: Church of the La Amistad freed slaves.

title: Fort Shantok Archeological District
desc: Mohegan settlement and home of the seventeenth century sachem Uncas.

title: Florence Griswold House and Museum
desc: Boarding house frequented by American impressionist artists such as Henry Ward Ranger, Childe Hassam, and Willard Metcalf.

title: Grove Street Cemetery
desc: Final resting place of many Yale and New Haven notables including Roger Sherman, Noah Webster and Eli Whitney.

title: Hill-Stead
desc: Colonial revival house and art museum located in the Farmington Historic District

title: Samuel Huntington Birthplace
desc: Boyhood saltbox home of the American statesman Samuel Huntington, a signer of the Declaration of Independence, Governor of Connecticut and first presiding officer of the Congress of the Confederation

title: Philip Johnson Glass House
desc: Modern masterpiece of glass and steel; designed and occupied by architect Philip Johnson.

title: Kimberly Mansion
desc: Home of Abby and Julia Smith, suffragists who successfully fought the town of Glastonbury on the issue of taxation without representation.

title: L. A. Dunton (schooner)
desc: Classic fishing schooner and one of the last sail-powered fishing vessels built.

title: Litchfield Historic District
desc: Well-preserved late 18th-early 19th century New England town that was the state's first historic district.

title: Lockwood-Mathews Mansion
desc: Second Empire style mansion built in 1864.

title: Othniel C. Marsh House
desc: Home of Yale paleontologist Othniel Marsh; now part of the Yale School of Forestry (Marsh Hall).

title: Mashantucket Pequot Reservation Archeological District
desc: Expansive district on the Mashantucket Pequot Reservation containing archaeological remains relevant to Pequot history.

title: Stephen Tyng Mather Home
desc: Home of conservationist Stephen Tyng Mather, who was instrumental in the formation of the National Park Service and served as its first director.

title: Lafayette B. Mendel House
desc: Home of Yale biochemist Lafayette Mendel; designed by Henry Austin

title: Monte Cristo Cottage(Eugene O'Neill House)
desc: Home of the Nobel prize-winning playwright Eugene O'Neill.

title: Edward W. Morley House

By 1944 this command was responsible for the supply and administration of all U.S. Army personnel in the Central and South Pacific, and from 1943 to 1945, carried out logistical planning for the invasions of the Gilberts, Marshalls, Marianas, Guam, Palau, and Okinawa.

title: Wheeler Field
desc: Another primary target during the attack on Pearl Harbor, the damage caused here allowed the Japanese to maintain air superiority during the attack.

title: Bear River Massacre Site
desc: Where California Volunteers wrought Bear River Massacre upon a Shoshoni village in 1863.

title: Camas Meadows Battle Sites
desc: Sites of the Battle of Camas Creek, which allowed Nez Perce to further elude capture.

title: Cataldo Mission
desc: This Jesuit mission to the Coeur d'Alenes, dating from the 1850s, is the oldest remaining mission church in the Pacific Northwest.

title: City of Rocks
desc: Thousands of emigrants on the California Trail made this a popular resting point, and left wagon ruts that are still visible today. For these emigrants, the landscape of rock outcrops rising like city buildings, woodlands, and mountains provided a welcome change from the surrounding sagebrush plains.

title: Experimental Breeder Reactor No.1
desc: This pioneering nuclear reactor was the site of several milestones in the development of nuclear technology, including the first usable electricity (1951), the first self-sustaining chain reaction using plutonium rather than uranium (1963), and the first demonstration of the feasible use of high-temperature liquid metal as a reactor coolant.

title: Fort Hall
desc: Outpost where the Oregon Trail forked, splitting off the California Trail.

title: Lemhi Pass
desc: Pass crossed by the Lewis and Clark Expedition in August 1805

title: Lolo Trail
desc: Difficult trail followed by the Lewis and Clark Expedition in 1805 and returning in 1806.

title: Weippe Prairie
desc: Meadow of camas, whose roots were basic food for Nez Perce, where the Lewis and Clark Expedition emerged from Lolo Trail.

title: Mary McLeod Bethune Home
desc: Home of Mary McLeod Bethune, educator and civil rights leader[9]

title: Bok Tower Gardens
desc: Constructed by Ladies Home Journal editor Edward W. Bok on the highest hill in the area to create "a spot of beauty second to none in the country"[10]

title: British Fort
desc: Built during the War of 1812 and also known as Negro Fort, it was the location of a fortification occupied by runaway slaves, as well as Indians living in the area. Due to a massive explosion near the end of the war, nothing remains of the fort.[11]

title: Cape Canaveral Air Force Station
desc: The East Coast space launch facility of the U.S. Department of Defense, and adjacent to the Kennedy Space Center[12]

title: Cathedral Of St. Augustine
desc: Completed in 1797, it was severely damaged by fire in 1887, but restored over the next two years. It is part of the St. Augustine Town Plan Historic District[13]

title: Crystal River Site
desc: A ceremonial center and burial complex, occupied during the Deptford, Weeden Island, and Safety Harbor periods[14]

title: Dade Battlefield

title: Ferdinand Magellan - U.S. Car No. 1
desc: The first passenger railcar built for a President since the one made for Lincoln in 1865. It was used by FDR, Truman, Eisenhower, and briefly by Reagan.[17]

title: Florida Southern College Historic District
desc: Contains the largest single-site collection of Frank Lloyd Wright architecture.

title: Fort King Site
desc: Site of fort prominent before and during the Second Seminole War. It was located at a nexus of military roads reaching from Tampa to Jacksonville[18]

title: Fort Mose Site
desc: First free black settlement legally sanctioned in what would become the United States. Slaves from the British colonies of South Carolina and Georgia escaped here during the early to mid 18th century, making this a precursor to the Underground Railroad.[19]

title: Fort San Carlos De Barrancas
desc: Site of a series of forts going back as far as 1698, now part of the Gulf Islands National Seashore.[20]

title: Fort San Marcos De Apalache
desc: Wooden or masonry forts were at this site during Spanish or British colonial periods, and the Second Seminole War. The Spanish fort's capture in 1818 by Jackson led the U.S. to acquire Florida in 1821.[21]

title: Fort Walton Mound
desc: Type site of the Fort Walton Culture[22]

title: Fort Zachary Taylor
desc: Controlled by the Union during the Civil War, later used heavily during the Spanish-American War, it is now a state park[23]

title: Freedom Tower
desc: The original headquarters and printing facility of the Miami News & Metropolis newspaper; later made a memorial to Cuban immigration to the U.S.[25]

title: GonzÃ¡lez-Alvarez House
desc: The oldest house in St. Augustine, built in the early 18th century, and part of the St. Augustine Town Plan Historic District[26]

title: Governor Stone (schooner)
desc: Built in 1877, it is the oldest surviving Gulf-built two-masted coasting schooner[27]

title: Ernest Hemingway House
desc: A home of author Ernest Hemingway[28]

title: Hotel Ponce de Leon
desc: Built in 1887-88 by CarrÃ¨re and Hastings for real estate and railroad tycoon Henry Flagler, it is the first large scale building constructed entirely of poured concrete. The only Flagler Hotel to survive the Great Depression, it later became part of Flagler College. Part of St. Augustine Town Plan Historic District[29]

title: Zora Neale Hurston House
desc: A home of author Zora Neale Hurston[30]

title: INGHAM (USCGC)
desc: Built at Philadelphia Naval Shipyard in 1935 and launched in 1936. Served on North Atlantic Convoys and credited with sinking u-boat 626. Served in Mediterranean and African Convoys and then landings in the Philippines. Served through Korea and received two Presidential Unit Citations for service in Viet-Nam. Served in Key West during the Mariel Boat lift in 1980 and retired in 1988 after 52 years of service. She remains the most decorated cutter in Coast Guard History.

title: Llambias House
desc: Built in the late 18th century, and part of the St. Augustine Town Plan Historic District[31]

title: Maitland Art Center
desc: Artist J. Andre Smith founded the Center as an artist colony in 1937. With over 200 carvings and reliefs, it is an important example of Art Deco fantasy and Mayan Revival architecture in the United States.[32]

title: MAPLE LEAF (shipwreck)
desc: Launched in 1851, it was sunk by the Confederates in 1864, and is one of the best preserved Civil War shipwrecks[33]

title: Mar-A-Lago

title: Miami Biltmore Hotel & Country Club

title: The Miami Circle at Brickell Point Site

title: Mud Lake Canal

title: Pelican Island National Wildlife Refuge

title: Pensacola Naval Air Station Historic District

title: Plaza Ferdinand VII
desc: Place where Florida was formally transferred from Spain to the U.S., in 1821[41]

title: Ponce de Leon Inlet Light Station

title: Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings House and Farm Yard

title: Traveler's Rest
desc: Early tavern and inn
