county:
Missoula, MT, Clear-
water, ID, and Idaho, ID

title: Northeast Entrance Station
desc: Rustic entrance station built in 1935 that is a prime example of form fitting function, in Yellowstone National Park.

title: Pictograph Cave
desc: One of the key archeological sites used in determining the sequence of prehistoric occupation on the northwestern Plains. The deposits indicate occupation from 2600 BC to after 1800 AD.[13]

title: Pompey's Pillar
desc: The massive natural block of sandstone was a major landmark on the Lewis and Clark Expedition. Clark's signature is carved on its surface.[14]

title: Rankin Ranch
desc: Residence (1923â€“56) of Jeannette Rankin, first woman elected to U.S. House of Representatives (1916), had two terms 1917-19 & 1941-43, only member to oppose the declaration of war against Japan in 1941.[15]

title: Rosebud Battlefield-Where the Girl Saved Her Brother
desc: Site of the Battle of the Rosebud[16]

title: Charles M. Russell House and Studio
desc: Home and studio of artist Charles M. Russell.[17]

title: Three Forks of the Missouri
desc: Captain William Clark of the Lewis and Clark Expedition, first European-American to visit this spot, concluded the Missouri River originated where the Three Forks joined.[18]

title: Travelers Rest
desc: Campsite used during the westward passage of the Lewis and Clark Expedition in 1805 as the party prepared to cross the Bitterroot Mountains, and again during return passage in 1806.

title: Virginia City Historic District
desc: More than 200 historic 19th century buildings remain in this 1860s mining town; it also served as the Montana Territorial Capitol during the same period.

title: Burton K. Wheeler House
desc: Former residence of noted Montana Senator Burton K. Wheeler.[19]

title: Wolf Mountains Battlefield-Where Big Crow walked Back and Forth
desc: Site of the Battle of Wolf Mountain.[20]

title: Fort Churchill
desc: Fort Churchill, named for Sylvester Churchill, was a U.S. Army fort built in 1861 to provide protection for early settlers

title: Fort Ruby
desc: Fort built during the Civil War to protect links between the Union and California, via the Overland Trail. Landmark status is under review due to fire damage.

title: Hoover Dam
desc: Gravity-arch dam of the Colorado River. World's largest hydroelectric power producing facility and largest concrete structure, when completed in 1935.

title: Leonard Rockshelter
desc: Discovered in 1936, this is an archaeological site that shows settlement from 6700 BC up to 1400 AD.

title: McKeen Motor Car #70 (Virginia & Truckee Railway Motor Car #22)
desc: One of the few surviving McKeen railcars. Restored to operating condition in 2010.

title: Nevada Northern Railway, East Ely Yards
desc: The Nevada Northern is one of the best-preserved early twentieth-century railroad shop complexes remaining in the United States.

title: Francis G. Newlands Home
desc: This was the home of Francis G. Newlands from 1890 until his death in 1917, including his tenure in the House of Representatives and Senate. Newlands is known for the Reclamation Act of 1902, under which the U.S. government led the massive development of irrigation in the West.

title: Virginia City Historic District
desc: Virginia City was a prototype for frontier mining boom towns, owing its success to the 1859 discovery of Comstock Lode.

title: Ash Hollow Cave
desc: Included in Ash Hollow Historic District

title: William Jennings Bryan House
desc: The home of William Jennings Bryan.

title: Willa Cather House
desc: Author Willa Cather's childhood home

title: Coufal Site
desc: An archaeological site.

title: Father Flanagan's Boys' Home
desc: Site of Father Flanagan's original boy's home

title: Fort Atkinson
desc: Site of the original Council Bluffs

title: Fort Robinson and Red Cloud Agency
desc: Site of an Indian Wars-era U.S. Army post.

title: USS HAZARD (minesweeper)
desc: A ship located in Omaha's Freedom Park.

title: Leary Site
desc: An archaeological site.

title: J. Sterling Morton House
desc: The home J. Sterling Morton and the National Arbor Day Foundation.

title: Nebraska State Capitol
desc: The seat of the Government of Nebraska.

title: George W. Norris House
desc: Home of U.S. Senator George W. Norris.

title: Palmer Site
desc: An archaeological site.

title: Dr. Susan LaFlesche Picotte Memorial Hospital
desc: Hospital founded by Susan La Flesche Picotte, the first American Indian physician and one of the first female physicians in the U.S.

title: Pike Pawnee Village Site
desc: Claimed for the U.S. by Captain Zebulon Pike during the Pike expedition in 1806.

title: Robidoux Pass
desc: Pass that was part of the Oregon Trail from 1848 to 1851, when another pass became preferred.

title: Schultz Site
desc: An archaeological site.

title: Walker Gilmore Site
desc: An archaeological site.

title: Anheuser-Busch Brewery
desc: The buildings in Anheuser-Busch's brewing district date from the late 1800s and are made of brick. Many are decorated with gargoyles and other such figures on the exterior. In addition, the company has also added new buildings and renovated older ones, but the district's status as a historic site has not been compromised.[8]

title: Arrow Rock
desc: The crossing of the Missouri River at Arrow Rock, which was recorded in the 1700s, played an important role in early explorations, such as the Lewis and Clark expedition in 1804, that led to the opening of the American West. A ferry was later established near Arrow Rock, at what became a starting point for traders on the Santa Fe Trail. The district is now home to Arrow Rock State Park.[9]

title: George Caleb Bingham House
desc: George Caleb Bingham, a painter, lived in this house from 1837â€“1845. During his time at this house, Bingham first sketched the Missouri River and local frontier life that later turned into his "genre" works.[10]

title: Louis Bolduc House
desc: This home was the residence of Louis Bolduc from around 1785 until his death in 1815. Bolduc was a lead miner, merchant, and planter, and was one of the local leaders of Ste. Genevieve, a small town. The house itself is an example of one in the French Colonial style of poteaux-sur-solle, or posts on sill, with a stone foundation. It also utilizes bouzillage (clay and grass) as a wall filling.[11]

title: Carrington Osage Village Site
desc: This site was occupied by the Big Osage tribe of Native Americans from around 1775â€“1825, and was the group's last area of residence in the southwestern portion of Missouri, as they were later confined to a Kansas reservation. The site is representative of the culture of the Big Osage, because it appears to have been a major trading area for the tribe.[12]

title: Christ Church Cathedral
desc: Construction for the church began in 1859, but the structure was not completed until 1867. The Gothic Revival building was designed by architect Leopold Eidlitz, even though he was not devoted to the Gothic style.[13]

title: "Champ" Clark House
desc: This house served as the residence of James Beauchamp Clark from 1899 until his death in 1921. Clark was the Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives from 1911â€“1919.[14]

title: Eads Bridge
desc: This steel bridge was built in 1874, at a total length of 6,442 feet (1,964Â m). It was designed by Captain James B. Eads, who used a system of cantilevers to allow for the bridge's long length. At the time of its construction, the Eads Bridge was used primarily as a means to connect railroads running westward to Missouri and those running eastward to Illinois.[15]

title: Joseph Erlanger House
desc: This house was the home of Joseph Erlanger from 1917 until his death in 1965. Erlanger was an American physiologist and a co-recipient of the 1944 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine. More recently, the house fell into a state of disrepair because its owner was unable to maintain the structure.[16]

title: Field House
desc: This was the home of attorney Roswell Field, who represented slave Dred Scott in the U.S. Supreme Court case Scott v. Sandford (1857).[17] Also the birthplace of Field's son, author Eugene Field, the house is currently known as the Eugene Field House and St. Louis Toy Museum.[18]

title: Fort Osage
desc: This factory trading post was established by William Clark in 1808. Built for the protection of the Osage Indians, Fort Osage experienced success in as a trade house until the end of the factory system in 1822.[19]

title: Gateway Arch
desc: The tallest man-made monument in the U.S., the arch is based on a weighted catenary design conceived by Finnish American architect Eero Saarinen. In 1967, the 630 feet (190Â m) structure was opened to the public as part of the Jefferson National Expansion Memorial.[20][21]

title: Goldenrod (showboat)
desc: A rare remaining example of an early-1900s era showboat, this vessel once held 1,400 passengers. The Goldenrod Showboat featured entertainers in minstrel shows, vaudeville, or drama.[23]

title: Graham Cave
desc: In 1949, remnants of Archaic American civilization were found in this cave. Dating back to 8,000 B.C., these remains indicate a blending of Eastern and Plains cultures at Graham Cave, which is now part of Graham Cave State Park.[24]

title: Liberty Memorial
desc: This building of this memorial started with a group of about 40 citizens, a Memorial Association led by Robert A. Long, and a dedication to build a memorial to the fallen soldiers of WW I. With funding secured (a massive fund raising that brought in over 2.5 million dollars) and approval from the city council, construction began on November 1, 1921. The Groundbreaking ceremony was the first and last gathering a group of men that included: Lieutenant General Baron Jacques of Belgium, Marshal Ferdinand Foch of France, General Armando Diaz of Italy, Admiral Earl Beatty of Great Britain, and General John Pershing of the United States. The dedication, on November 11, 1926, was attended by U.S. President Calvin Coolidge. The Liberty Memorial is home to The National World War I Museum

title: Mutual Musicians Association Building
desc: Center of "Kansas City Style" of jazz

title: General John J. Pershing Boyhood Home
desc: A boyhood home of General John J. Pershing

title: Sanborn Field and Soil Erosion Plots
desc: Located on the University of Missouri campus the research conducted here helped establish soil conservation policy in the United States. The organism Streptomyces aureofaciens the original source of the drug Chlortetracycline (Aeruomycin), the first tetracycline antibiotic, was isolated here.

title: Mark Twain Boyhood Home
desc: A boyhood home of Mark Twain

title: United States Customhouse And Post Office
Washington University Hilltop Campus Historic District
Adams Academy
desc: High Gothic building, built in 1871 to a design by William Robert Ware and Henry Van Brunt, for a preparatory school funded with a bequest of John Adams.[3]

title: John Adams Birthplace
desc: This is the house in which United States President John Adams was born on October 30, 1735. It is now part of the Adams National Historical Park.[4][5]

title: John Quincy Adams Birthplace
desc: President John Quincy Adams was born in this house, which is adjacent to the John Adams Birthplace; it is also part of the Adams National Historical Park.[5][6]

title: Adventure
desc: This schooner is one of the last surviving Gloucester-based Grand Banks fishing schooners, and one of only two surviving "knockabout" fishing schooners.[7]

title: John and Priscilla Alden Family Sites
desc: These two sites in Duxbury are associated with John and Priscilla Alden, who were the inspiration for Henry Wadsworth Longfellow's The Courtship of Miles Standish.[8]

title: American Antiquarian Society
desc: This 1910 Georgian Revival building houses the American Antiquarian Society, the third oldest (1812) historical society in the United States and the first to be national in scope.[9]

title: Arrowhead (Herman Melville House)
desc: This 18th-century farmhouse was the home of author Herman Melville (1819â€“91) during his most productive years from 1850â€“1863. He wrote several novels here, including Moby-Dick, as well as short stories, magazine stories and poetry. The house is now a museum.[10]

title: Maria Baldwin House
desc: This 19th century duplex was the home of educator Maria Louise Baldwin (1856â€“1922), the first female African-American principal of a school in New England.[11][12]

title: Beauport
desc: Seminal interior designer and decorator Henry Davis Sleeper (1878â€“1934) used this Shingle-style as a showcase of his work. It is owned by Historic New England and operated as a museum.[13][14]

title: Edward Bellamy House
desc: This was the longtime home of journalist and social activist Edward Bellamy (1850â€“98), author of the utopian novel Looking Backward.[15]

title: George D. Birkhoff House
desc: This modest house was the home of George David Birkhoff (1884â€“1944), a leading mathematician of the early 20th century.[16]

title: Blue Hill Meteorological Observatory
desc: Described as "principal structure associated with the history of weather observation" in the United States, this observatory is home to the oldest continuous weather record in North America, and is where numerous meteorological measurement and analysis techniques were developed.[17]

title: Boardman House
desc: This house, whose early construction dates to the late 17th century, has remained little changed since the early 18th century. It is now a house museum operated by Historic New England.[18]

title: Boston Manufacturing Company
desc: This building housed the eponymous company, founded in 1813 by businessman Francis Cabot Lowell, engineer Paul Moody, and others, for the manufacture of cotton textiles. At this site the manufacture of textiles under a single roof was proved, a major success leading to the American Industrial Revolution.[19]

title: Nathaniel Bowditch Home
desc: This Federalist house was the home of Nathaniel Bowditch (1773â€“1838), the founder of modern (19th century) navigation.[20] It now serves as the headquarters of Historic Salem, Inc.[21]

title: Louis Brandeis House
desc: Bought in 1922 by liberal United States Supreme Court Justice Louis Brandeis (1856â€“1941), this Cape style house (whose construction dates to the late 19th century) was used by the Brandeis family as a summer retreat.[22]

title: Percy W. Bridgman House
desc: This house served as the longtime home of Nobel prize-winning physicist Percy W. Bridgman (1882â€“1961). His innovations in the field of high pressure physics made possible the development of synthetic diamonds.[23]

title: William Cullen Bryant Homestead
desc: This property was the boyhood home and later summer residence of poet and newspaper editor William Cullen Bryant (1794â€“1878). It is now owned by The Trustees of Reservations and operated as a house museum.[24]

title: Buckman Tavern
desc: The oldest of Lexington's inns (established c. 1690), local militiamen mustered here prior to the April 19, 1775 Battles of Lexington and Concord that began the American Revolutionary War.[25]

title: Cape Ann Light Station
desc: Located on Thacher Island, this light station was established in 1771, and was the last founded in the colonia era. The two lighthouses were the first to mark a navigational hazard (Thacher Island); the current lighthouses were constructed in 1861, and are aligned on a north-south axis.[26]

title: Parson Capen House
desc: This circa 1683 house was home to Reverend Joseph Capen, Topsfield's minister for many years. It is one of the best preserved 17th-century houses in the United States.[27] It is operated by the Topsfield Historical Society as a house museum.[28]

title: Castle Hill
desc: This early 20th-century country estate is one of the finest of its type. The house was designed by architect David Adler of Chicago, and the landscaping was done by the Olmsted Brothers firm, among others. The estate is owned by The Trustees of Reservations, and is open to the public.[29]

title: Christ Church
desc: This church, designed by architect Peter Harrison and completed in 1761, served Cambridge Anglicans. Despite numerous alterations, the church has retained much its original 18th century character.[30]

title: Jethro Coffin House
desc: This saltbox house, built in 1686, is the oldest surviving residential structure on Nantucket. It is now owned by the Nantucket Historical Association, which operates it as a house museum.[31]

title: Cole's Hill
desc: Cole's Hill is the site of the burial ground of the Pilgrims. Those who died in the first winter of the Plymouth Colony (1620â€“21) were buried there.[32]

title: Converse Memorial Library
desc: This public library building was the last such building designed by architect H. H. Richardson, and is counted among his greatest works.[33]

title: Crane and Company Old Stone Mill Rag Room
desc: From 1844 to 1930 this building was used as part of Crane and Company's paper manufacturing process, and is one of the nation's oldest surviving paper manufacturing buildings; it now houses Crane's museum. Crane has since 1879 been the exclusive supplier of paper for United States paper currency.[34]

title: Crane Memorial Library
desc: One of five public libraries designed by H. H. Richardson, he considered it to be one of his best designs. The building incorporates stained glass by John LaFarge and sculptural elements by Augustus Saint-Gaudens.[35]

title: Paul Cuffe Farm
desc: This site was the home and farm of Paul Cuffee (1759â€“1817), a wealthy colonial-era African-American merchant. Cuffee was a leading advocate for minority rights in Massachusetts, and a promoter and funder of the resettlement of African-Americans to present-day Sierra Leone.[36]

title: Caleb Cushing House
desc: This fine Federalist house was the home of diplomat and United States Attorney General Caleb Cushing (1800â€“79). Cushing is known for negotiating the 1844 Treaty of Wanghia, the first treaty between the United States and Qing China, and other diplomatic successes. The house now serves as the headquarters of the local historical society.[37]

title: Reginald A. Daly House
desc: This Queen Anne style house was the longtime home of geologist and Harvard University professor Reginald Aldworth Daly (1871â€“1957). Daly was a pioneer in the application of physics and chemistry to the field of geology.[38]

title: William M. Davis House
desc: This house was home to geologist and geographer William Morris Davis (1850â€“1934). Davis was a leading figure in the development of the study of geology, founding the Association of American Geographers and developing the first model of the cycle of erosion.[39][40]

title: Derby Summer House
desc: This is a rare example of an 18th-century American garden house. Designed in the 1790s by Samuel McIntire, it resided on the estate of Salem merchant Elias Hasket Derby until 1901, when it was moved to the Endicott family's Glen Magna Farms country estate. The estate, now owned by the Danvers Historical Society, is open to the public.[41][42]

title: Emily Dickinson Home
desc: This house was home of the reclusive poet Emily Dickinson (1830â€“86) for most of her life. The house is now owned by Amherst College and is operated as a house museum.[43][44]

title: W.E.B. Dubois Boyhood Homesite
desc: This site contains all that remains of the childhood home of African American intellectual and activist W.E.B. Du Bois (1868â€“1963). The property, which belonged to his family for over 200 years, is seasonally open to the public.[45][46]

title: Elmwood
desc: This 1760s Georgian house and estate was home to three historically important individuals: Massachusetts colonial Lieutenant Governor Thomas Oliver (who had the house built), Massachusetts Governor and US Vice President Elbridge Gerry, and poet James Russell Lowell, who gave the property its name. It now serves as the home of the Harvard University president.[47][48]

title: Ralph Waldo Emerson Home
desc: This house was purchased by writer, poet, and philosopher Ralph Waldo Emerson (1803â€“1882) in 1835. It was where he wrote all of his major works, and was a major meeting point for Transcendentalists, including Bronson Alcott and Henry David Thoreau. It has been a house museum since 1930.[49]

title: Ernestina (schooner)
desc: Ernestina is the oldest surviving Grand Banks fishing schooner, and the only surviving 19th century fishing schooner built in Gloucester. Owned by the state and under the overall aegis of the New Bedford Whaling National Historical Park, she is in 2012 sidelined from her intended educational purpose by budget constraints and the need for repairs.[50][51]

title: Fairbanks House
desc: Continuously owned by a single family since its construction in the late 1630s, this is probably the oldest timber-frame house in North America. It is now operated by Fairbanks Family in America, Inc., as a house museum.[52]

title: Reginald A. Fessenden House
desc: Reginald Fessenden (1866â€“1932) was an inventor who worked for a time in Thomas Edison's workshop. His most notable inventions made possible the transmission of audio sounds via radio waves, and included many other radio-related innovations. This house was his last home; he was described in memoriam as "the greatest wireless inventor of the age."[53]

title: First Church Of Christ, Lancaster
desc: One of the finest churches designed by architect Charles Bulfinch, this building was constructed in 1816 and is occupied by a congregation whose history dates to 1653.[54][55]

title: Flying Horses Carousel
desc: This carousel, one of two extant examples of the work of the Charles F. W. Dare Company, is the oldest operating platform carousel in the nation, and may be the oldest of any type (the Flying Horse Carousel of Watch Hill, Rhode Island, also built by the Dare Company, is possibly older).[56]

title: Capt. R.B. Forbes House
desc: Designed by Isaiah Rogers, this 1833 Greek Revival house was built by ship captain and China Trade merchant Robert Bennet Forbes and his siblings for their mother. Furnished and decorated with acquisitions Forbes made in China, it is now a house museum.[57][58]

title: Daniel Chester French Home and Studio
desc: Better known as Chesterwood, this was the summer home and studio of sculptor Daniel Chester French (1850â€“1931) from 1891 until his death. The estate was designed by French's collaborator Henry Bacon, and is now owned by the National Trust for Historic Preservation. It is open to the public on a seasonal basis.[59][60]

title: Fruitlands
desc: Fruitlands was the site of a short-lived (1843â€“44) Transcendentalist utopian community founded by Amos Bronson Alcott.[61] The property was acquired by preservationist Clara Endicott Sears in 1910 and opened as the Fruitlands Museum four years later.[62]

title: Margaret Fuller House
desc: This was the birthplace and childhood home of Transcendentalist and feminist Margaret Fuller (1810â€“50). Her Woman in the Nineteenth Century is one of the earliest statements of feminist thought.[63][64]

title: Gardner-Pingree House
desc: Salem merchant John Gardner had this Federalist-style house built in 1804â€“05 by Samuel McIntire.[65] It was the site of a notorious murder in 1841 that inspired Nathaniel Hawthorne and Edgar Allan Poe.[66] It is now owned by the Peabody Essex Museum, which offers guided tours.[67]

title: General John Glover House
desc: John Glover (1732â€“97) had this simple frame house built in 1762, and occupied until 1782.[68] Glover, a wealthy Marblehead merchant, was an important military figure in the American Revolutionary War, leading the Marblehead Regiment early in the war as well as leading early efforts to establish the Continental Navy.[69]

title: Goddard Rocket Launching Site
desc: This site, located on a local golf course, is where rocket scientist Robert H. Goddard launched the first liquid-fueled rocket in 1926.[70] The actual launch site is marked by a granite obelisk.[71]

title: Gore Place
desc: A remnant of an estate that was once much larger, Gore Place preserves an excellent Federalist mansion built in 1806 for Christopher Gore, a Massachusetts governor and United States senator. The mansion was saved from destruction in 1935, and is now open to the public as a house museum.[72]

title: John B. Gough House
desc: This Italianate house, also known as "Hillside", was the home of orator John B. Gough (1817â€“86), a leading figure of the 19th century temperance movement. The estate, owned by the town of Boylston, is undergoing a lengthy restoration and conservation process.[73][74]

title: Asa Gray House
desc: This Federalist house, designed by Ithiel Town and built in 1810, most notably served as the longtime home of botanist and Harvard professor Asa Gray (1810â€“88). Gray was one of the most important botanists of the 19th century, publishing works still referenced today and defending Charles Darwin's On the Origin of Species.[75]

title: Gropius House
desc: Bauhaus architect Walter Gropius designed this house in 1937 as a personal expression of Modernism, living in it until his death in 1969. Owned by Historic New England and operated as a house museum, it contains the most important collection of Bauhaus artifacts outside Germany.[76][77]

title: H. H. Richardson Historic District of North Easton
desc: This landmark district contains five buildings in Easton designed by architect H. H. Richardson and landscaped by Frederick Law Olmsted, primarily through the efforts of the wealthy Ames family: Oakes Ames Memorial Hall, the Ames Free Library, the Old Colony Railroad Station, and two nearby structures on the Langwater estate of Frederick Lothrop Ames.[78]

title: Hamilton Hall
desc: Named for Federalist Party leader Alexander Hamilton, this 1805 building was designed by Samuel McIntire to serve Salem's Federalist Party activities. It has been described as "one of the most outstanding Federal-era public buildings" in the nation.[79]

title: Hancock-Clarke House
desc: This 1737 house was the boyhood home of Revolutionary leader John Hancock, and was where he and Samuel Adams hid from British authorities at the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War.[80] It is now owned by the Lexington Historical Society, and is seasonally open to the public.[81]

title: Hancock Shaker Village
desc: This Shaker village was established in 1791 and lasted until 1960, after which it became a living history museum. It is noted for its distinctive round barn, built in 1826.[82][83]

title: Oliver Hastings House
desc: This Greek Revival house was built in 1844 as the home of Cambridge businessman Oliver Hastings (1791â€“1879). Although nearby resident Charles Sanders Peirce considered it "ugly", the building is recognized for its elegant curved bays and elaborate wrought iron balcony railings.[84][85]

title: Oliver Wendell Holmes House
desc: This 1877 frame house was the summer home of United States Supreme Court Associate Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr. (1841â€“1935). Holmes is known for his longevity on the bench, and his opinions on freedom of speech.[86][87]

title: House of the Seven Gables
desc: Best known for its association with Nathaniel Hawthorne's novel of the same name, this 1668 house was also a key early preservation effort, successfully restored in the early 20th century by historian and preservationist Joseph Everett Chandler. The district, which includes several other historical buildings, has been operated ever since as a history museum.[88]

title: Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival
desc: Jacob's Pillow was founded in 1931 by Ted Shawn as a place to develop an all-male dance company. It has since trained generations of dance professionals of all types, and continues to stage productions every summer.[89]

title: Nathan and Mary (Polly) Johnson properties
desc: These buildings, now housing the New Bedford Historical Society, belonged to a free African-American couple active in the abolitionist movement and the Underground Railroad. They notably took in activist Frederick Douglass after his escape from slavery.[90]

title: USS Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr. (destroyer)
desc: The only surviving United States Navy Gearing-class destroyer, this vessel is named for Joseph P. Kennedy, Jr. (the brother of future President John F. Kennedy) who was killed in action during World War II.[91] It is on display at Fall River's Battleship Cove.[92]

title: Kennedy Compound
desc: This compound consists of three residences, each belonging at some point to Joseph P. Kennedy, Sr., diplomat and patriarch of the politically influential Kennedy family, or one his sons: President John F. Kennedy, Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy, and Senator Edward M. Kennedy.[93]

title: John F. Kennedy Birthplace
desc: Now a National Historic Site, this modest suburban house was the birthplace and childhood home of President John F. Kennedy (1917â€“63).[94]

title: Jeremiah Lee House
desc: Jeremiah Lee was the wealthiest merchant in Massachusetts in the 1760s, when he had this Georgian mansion built. The mansion is in a remarkable state of preservation, and is operated by the local historical society as a house museum.[95]

title: Lexington Green
desc: Lexington's town common, it was here that opening skirmish of the American Revolutionary War took place on April 19, 1775.[96]

title: Liberty Farm
desc: This house belonged to abolitionists and suffragists Abby Kelley Foster (1811â€“87) and Stephen Symonds Foster (1809â€“81), and was used by them as a site on the Underground Railroad. The property also featured prominently in the Fosters' refusal to pay property taxes because she was unable to vote.[97]

title: General Benjamin Lincoln House
desc: This well-preserved 18th-century house was the birthplace and lifelong home of Revolutionary War General and Massachusetts Lieutenant Governor Benjamin Lincoln (1733â€“1810). The house, which is not open to the public, remains in Lincoln family hands.[98]

title: USS Lionfish (submarine)
desc: An intact Balao-class submarine, USS Lionfish served two tours of duty in the Pacific during World War II and served as a training vessel before being decommissioned and placed on display at Battleship Cove.[99]

title: Arthur D. Little Inc., Building
desc: This unremarkable 1917 office building was the site of the nation's first successful independent consulting laboratory, Arthur D. Little. The company pioneered the idea of commercial laboratories as independent, profit-making businesses.[100]

title: Henry Cabot Lodge Residence
desc: Henry Cabot Lodge (1850â€“1924) was a lifelong resident of this house. Lodge, as United States Senator from Massachusetts, was a critical voice in foreign policy debates of the early 20th century; he supported a wider role for the United States on the world stage, but led the opposition to ratification of the 1919 Treaty of Versailles that ended World War I.[101]

title: Longfellow House
desc: This 1759 Georgian house was used by George Washington as his residence during the 1775â€“76 Siege of Boston. In the 19th century it was purchased for poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow (1807â€“82) by his father-in-law, and is where Longfellow wrote many of his best-known works.[102]

title: Lowell Locks and Canals Historic District
desc: Lowell was the nation's first major industrialized city. Its system of canals and waterworks was constructed between 1794 and 1848. Most of these were built to power the large number of industries that sprang up in Lowell during the early years of the American Industrial Revolution, and remain in remarkable condition despite their age.[103]

title: Lowell's Boat Shop
desc: Founded in 1793, this boatshop has been in continuous business ever since; it is where founder Simeon Lowell developed the stackable dory. The present buildings date from the 1860s.[104]

title: USS Massachusetts (battleship)
desc: One of two surviving United States Navy South Dakota-class battleships, Massachusetts saw action in World War II, winning 11 battle stars. She is on display at Battleship Cove.[105]

title: Massachusetts Hall, Harvard University
desc: This building, now housing administrative offices and a freshman dormitory, is the oldest surviving building (1718â€“20) on the campus of Harvard University, and the second oldest academic building in the nation.[106][107]

title: Memorial Hall, Harvard University
desc: Designed by William Robert Ware and Henry Van Brunt, this High Gothic hall was built in the 1870s as Harvard University's memorial to its fallen in the American Civil War. Its amenities include Annenberg Hall (a dining hall) and Sanders Theater, a performance space.[108]

title: George R. Minot House
desc: George R. Minot (1885â€“1950) was awarded a Nobel Prize for his work finding a treatment for pernicious anemia, then a fatal disease. This 1920s suburban house was his home from 1929 until his death.[109]

title: Mission House
desc: This house was built in c. 1742 by Reverend John Sergeant, the first Christian missionary to the Stockbridge Indians. It is now owned and operated by The Trustees of Reservations as a house museum.[110]

title: The Mount (Edith Warton Estate)
desc: Designed by writer Edith Wharton (1862â€“1937) and built in 1902, The Mount is where she wrote the bestselling novel The House of Mirth. It is now a house museum.[111][112]

title: Mount Auburn Cemetery
desc: In an effort spearheaded by Dr. Jacob Bigelow, Mount Auburn Cemetery was laid out by Henry A. S. Dearborn in 1831 as "America's first garden cemetery". In addition to being the burial place of many famous Bostonians, it is known for its horticulture and as a birdwatching destination.[113]

title: Nantucket Historic District
desc: This listing, which encompasses the entire island of Nantucket, was made in recognition of Nantucket's well-preserved historical settlements (dating to the 17th century), and its importance as the world's preeminent whaling center in the early years of the 19th century.[114]

title: Naumkeag
desc: This Gilded Age mansion and country estate was designed by McKim, Mead & White, with landscaping by Fletcher Steele. Built in the 1880s for lawyer Joseph Choate, it was given by his daughter to The Trustees of Reservations, who operate it as a museum.[115]

title: Nauset Archeological District
desc: This district, located within the southern portion of the Cape Cod National Seashore, encompasses sites containing substantial ancient settlements dating to at least 4,000 BC. Some of these sites were described in the chronicles of early European explorers.[116]

title: New Bedford Historic District
desc: This district encompasses the historic center of the country's leading 19th century whaling center, including as contributing properties other historic landmarks.[117]

title: Norfolk County Courthouse
desc: This Greek Revival courthouse was built in 1827 and expanded over the 19th century. It was site of the controversial Sacco-Vanzetti trial in 1921, and has changed little since then.[118]

title: Old Deerfield Historic District
desc: This well-preserved 18th century colonial village was the site of numerous Indian raids, including a famous and well-documented attack in 1704.[119] The village is administed by Historic Deerfield as a museum.[120]

title: Old Manse
desc: This 1770 Revolutionary-era house was home for a time to both Ralph Waldo Emerson (whose grandfather had it built) and Nathaniel Hawthorne; Henry David Thoreau was a guest of Hawthorne's. The house is now owned by The Trustees of Reservations and is open to the public.[121]

title: Old Ship Meetinghouse
desc: This Puritan meetinghouse was constructed in 1681 and is claimed to be the oldest church in the nation still used for religious services.[122] Its name derives from its construction, which resembles an inverted wooden ship hull.[123]

title: Frederick Law Olmsted House
desc: Frederick Law Olmsted (1822â€“1903), one of America's leading landscape designers of his generation, lived and worked at this site for the last twenty years of his life.[124] It is now a National Historic Site.[125]

title: Orchard House
desc: This early 18th-century house was the longtime home of Transcendentalist Amos Bronson Alcott (1799â€“1888). His daughter, writer Louisa May Alcott, set the novel Little Women here. It is now a house museum.[126]

title: Robert Treat Paine House
desc: Also known as Stonehurst, this city-owned estate was designed by H. H. Richardson with landscaping by Frederick Law Olmsted for Boston lawyer Robert Treat Paine, Jr. (1835â€“1910). It is open to the public.[127]

title: The Parsonage
desc: This 1824 house was home to the father of writer Horatio Alger (1832â€“99). Alger, a prolific and popular writer of juvenile fiction, frequently summered here.[128]

title: Peabody Museum of Salem
desc: Now embedded within the Peabody Essex Museum, the East India Marine Hall was built in the 1820s. The museum traces its lineage to the 1799 East India Marine Society, claiming to be the nation's oldest continuously operating museum.[129]

title: Peirce-Nichols House
desc: This transitional Georgian/Federal style home was built in 1782 for merchant Jerathmiel Peirce by Samuel McIntire.[130] The house is owned by the Peabody Essex Museum, which offers tours.[131]

title: Lydia Pinkham House
desc: This 1872 Second Empire house was the residence of Lydia Pinkham, whose homemade herbal remedy for dysmenorrhea was one of the bestselling such medical products of the late 19th century thanks to Pinkham's use of her own image as a marketing tool. Orders and other correspondence were received at the house's Western Avenue address; sometimes Pinkham wrote back personally, a practice continued by her company after her death.[132]

title: PT 617
desc: The only surviving 80 feet (24Â m) Elco torpedo boat from World War II, craft of this type were workhoses throughout many theaters of the war. This boat is on display at the PT Boat Museum in Battleship Cove.[133]

title: PT 796
desc: This is one of three surviving Higgins PT boats, built late in World War II. It is on display at the PT Boat Museum in Battleship Cove.[134]

title: General Rufus Putnam House
desc: Rufus Putnam (1738â€“1824) was a Continental Army officer in the American Revolutionary War. After the war he pioneered the settlement of the Northwest Territories, serving as its first Surveyor General. This house, built in the early 1760s, was his home in the 1780s. Although it was for a time a local museum, it is now a bed and breakfast.[135][136]

title: Quincy Homestead
desc: This house was built in 1686 as an early home of the Quincy family. Its well-preserved construction documents 300 years of architectural changes. The building was an early success in house preservation early in the 20th century, and is now a house museum.[137][138]

title: Josiah Quincy House
desc: This house, built c. 1770, was occupied by a succession of politically active Quincys, and contains architectural details unique among houses from the period. It is owned by Historic New England, who offer infrequent tours during the summer months.[139][140]

title: Red Top (William Dean Howells' House)
desc: William Dean Howells (1837â€“1920) was a major literary figure of the late 19th century, writing prolifically and editing the Atlantic Monthly. This house was designed by Howells' brother-in-law William Rutherford Mead[141] (of McKim, Mead, and White), and was home to the Howellses 1878â€“1882. It was the site of gatherings involving many literary notables.[142]

title: Revere Beach Reservation
desc: Revere Beach was the first oceanside beach purchased for public access (in 1895). Noted architect Charles Eliot was responsible for the design and layout of the beach's roadways and facilities. Managed by the Massachusetts Department of Conservation and Recreation, the reservation continues to provide public recreation facilities.[143][144]

title: Theodore W. Richards House
desc: Theodore William Richards (1868â€“1928) was considered the foremost experimental chemist of his time. He won the Nobel prize for his role in determine the atomic weights of many elements. This house was built in 1900 with design input from Richards, and he lived there until his death.[145]

title: William J. Rotch Gothic Cottage
desc: This early Gothic Revival cottage was designed by Alexander Jackson Davis in 1845 for William J. Rotch (1819â€“1893), scion of New Bedford's leading whaling family. It exhibits features not found in other surviving similar works by Davis, and received wide public notice after its construction. The cottage is a private residence and is not open to the public.[146]

title: William Rotch, Jr. House
desc: This house was the first design of Richard Upjohn, a leading architect of the 19th century. He designed this Greek Revival home for William Rotch, Jr. (1759â€“1850), the leading whaling businessman of the time. Later residents of the house were also leading New Bedford figures. The property is now a house museum.[147]

title: Isaac Royall House
desc: This c. 1692 house was extensively expanded in the 18th century by merchant and slaveowner Isaac Royall, Jr. It was occupied by John Stark during the 1775â€“76 Siege of Boston. A well-preserved Georgian house that is now a museum, the property includes the only known surviving slave quarters in the northeastern United States.[148][149]

title: Count Rumford Birthplace
desc: Inventor and scientist Benjamin Thompson (1753â€“1814) was born in this well-preserved 1714 house. Thompson was lauded in Europe for his discoveries (including key advances in the field of thermodynamics); he received honors including the title Count Rumford. The house is now a museum.[150]

title: Saugus Iron Works
desc: This National Historic Site preserves an early colonial ironworks, dating to 1646.[151]

title: Sever Hall, Harvard University
desc: This mature work of H. H. Richardson is a classroom building. Richardson sought to integrate contemporary ideas of architecture into Harvard's largely Georgian campus.[152]

title: Spencer-Pierce-Little House
desc: This house is a rare example of a 17th-century stone house in New England. Relatively unchanged despite additions over the centuries, it is now owned by Historic New England, who operate the site as a farm and museum.[153][154]

title: Springfield Armory
desc: Until 1968 this site was a part of the nation's first armories and weapons production facilities, and a major military research facility. It was a focal point of the 1787 Shays' Rebellion, a local uprising against oppressive state fiscal policies.[155]

title: Joseph Story House
desc: Joseph Story (1779â€“1845) was an influential United States Supreme Court Justice on the John Marshall court. Story's jurisprudence and legal thought were highly influential during his tenure on the court (1811â€“45). Story lived in this Federalist style home from 1811 to 1829.[156]

title: Mary Fisk Stoughton House
desc: This 1880s Shingle style home by H. H. Richardson was one of his last commissions, and the best surviving example of his work in that style. The house's residents included Harvard University professor and historian John Fiske.[157]

title: Elihu Thomson House
desc: Elihu Thomson (1853â€“1937) was an inventor and pioneer in the field of electrical engineering. Along with Thomas Alva Edison he founded General Electric. This 1889 Georgian Revival house was Thomson's home for many years; it now serves as Swampscott's town hall.[158]

title: Peter Tufts House
desc: This house, whose construction date is uncertain but believed to be in the mid-to-late 17th century, is quite possibly the oldest brick house in North America. It was probably built by Peter Tufts (1628â€“1702), an early settler of Medford.[159] It is owned by the Medford Historical Society, which seasonally offers tours.[160]

title: United First Parish Church (Unitarian) Of Quincy
desc: Alexander Parris designed this Greek Revival church in the 1820s for the oldest congregation in Quincy. Presidents John Adams and John Quincy Adams are buried here.[161]

title: United States Customhouse
desc: This outstanding example of a public building in the Greek Revival style has been used as a customs facility since 1834.[162]

title: University Hall, Harvard University
desc: Architect Charles Bulfinch designed, and engineer Loammi Baldwin, Jr. constructed this Harvard College facility. Originally used for classes and dining, it now houses the administrative offices.[163]

title: The Vale
desc: Now more commonly called the Lyman Estate, this was the country estate of Boston merchant Theodore Lyman. Built in 1793, it includes one of the nation's oldest greenhouses, and has survived with most of its landscaping intact. It is open ot the public.[164][165]

title: Walden Pond
desc: Now part of a state reservation, Henry David Thoreau's cabin was located here. The time Thoreau spent here was inspiration for his conservationist treatise Walden.[166]

title: John Ward House
desc: Construction was begun on this house in 1684, with owner John Ward making several modifications to it prior to his death. The building, now owned by the Peabody Essex Museum, stands as a fine example of the organic growth of early colonial houses.[167]

title: The Wayside, "Home of Authors"
desc: This c. 1700 house, part of the Minuteman National Historical Park, was home to three writers in the 19th century: Louisa May Alcott, Nathaniel Hawthorne, and Margaret Sidney. The Park Service opens the house for tours seasonally.[168]

title: Daniel Webster Law Office
desc: Lawyer, politician, and orator Daniel Webster (1782â€“1852) used this 1832 cottage as his office and library. Originally located on his Marshfield estate, it is now on the grounds of the nearby Isaac Winslow House Museum.[169][170]

title: Wesleyan Grove
desc: Wesleyan Grove is a Methodist camp meeting established in 1835. Its grounds, which are open to the public, feature a large number of Victorian era gingerbread cottages. As one of the earliest camps of this type, its features were influential in the development of other permanent camp meeting facilities.[171]

title: John Whipple House
desc: The earliest portions of this house date to 1642. It has been operated as a museum (now known as the Ipswich Museum) since the 1890s.[172][173]

title: John Greenleaf Whittier Home
desc: This house was the longtime home of poet and abolitionist John Greenleaf Whittier (1807â€“92). It is now a house museum.[174]

title: Winn Memorial Library
desc: This was the first public library building designed by H. H. Richardson; it was built between 1876 and 1879. It still houses Woburn's public library.[175]

title: Wright's Tavern
desc: Wright's Tavern was used in October 1774 as the first meeting place of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress. In April 1775 it was the assembly point for Concord's Minutemen before the Battles of Lexington and Concord.[176]

title: Crater Lake Superintendent's Residence

title: Deady and Villard Halls, University of Oregon

Deady Hall is simplified Italianate in design with mansarded main roof and towers; Villard Hall has Second Empire touches, and is one of the few surviving academic buildings of its era in the Western United States.

title: Fort Astoria Site

The fort subsequently became an important part of the American territorial claim to the Oregon Country. Astor sold the fort to the British North West Company in 1813.

title: Fort Rock Cave

title: Jacksonville Historic District
desc: Founded in 1852 as a mining town, Jacksonville became the principal financial and commercial center of southern Oregon until it was bypassed by the railroad. Its group of surviving, unaltered commercial and residential buildings spans the full range of architectural styles employed in the West between 1850 and 1890. The town's unusual state of preservation and completeness make it a uniquely intact example of a mid-19th century inland commercial town.[6]

title: Kam Wah Chung Company Building
desc: This building is the best known example of a Chinese mercantile and herb store in the United States. It embodies the role of immigrant Chinese in the post-Civil War expansion period of the western United States.

title: Lightship WAL-604, "Columbia"
desc: Retired in 1979 as the last lightship to be stationed at the Columbia River Bar â€” or anywhere on the Pacific coast of the United States â€” WAL-604 retains the best historic integrity of the last generation of U.S. Coast Guard lightships after 1939. WAL-604, built in 1950, and its relatives closely resembled earlier lightship types in external appearance, but were a distinct departure in their overall design.

title: Lower Klamath National Wildlife Refuge
desc: This national wildlife refuge, established in 1908, was the first large block of public land set aside for wildlife management purposes. Because of the refuge's extensive overlap with the Klamath Basin water reclamation project, it has become an ongoing example of the tensions between conservation and economic demands in public land management.

title: Oregon Caves Chateau

title: Pioneer Courthouse
