desc: Located in what is now Tulpehocken Creek Park.

title: I. N. and Bernardine Hagan House
desc: A higher end Usonian house of those designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.

title: Harmony Historic District
desc: Associated with Harmony Society and George Rapp.

title: Harrisburg Station and Trainshed
desc: Pennsylvania Railroad station with sheds using truss system patented by Albert Fink.

title: Milton S. Hershey Mansion
desc: A home of Milton Snavely Hershey.

title: Horseshoe Curve
desc: A horseshoe-shaped railroad track

title: Kennywood Park
desc: From trolley park era, One of America's first amusement parks.

title: Leap-The-Dips
desc: The first rollercoaster still standing in the United States.

title: F. Julius Lemoyne House
desc: A home of F. Julius LeMoyne, involved with the Underground Railroad

title: Lightfoot Mill
desc: See also Oliver Evans.

title: Lukens Historic District
desc: Associated with Rebecca Lukens and Brandywine Ironworks (later Lukens Steel Company).

title: Humphry Marshall House
desc: A home of Humphry Marshall.

title: Meadowcroft Rockshelter
desc: Archaeological site associated with Native Americans.

title: Isaac Meason House
desc: A home of Isaac Meason.

title: Merion Cricket Club
desc: From when cricket competed with baseball for American attention.

title: Merion Golf Club
desc: Associated with Bobby Jones, who won the Grand Slam of Golf here in 1930. Host of many U.S. Opens.

title: Mill Grove
desc: A home of John James Audubon.

title: Minisink Archeological Site
desc: Prehistoric native site; extends into New Jersey.

title: George Nakashima Woodworker Complex
desc: Art studio and home of woodworker George Nakashima

title: Old Economy
desc: Associated with Harmony Society and George Rapp.

title: Old West, Dickinson College
desc: Designed by Benjamin H. Latrobe, part of Dickinson College which was founded by Benjamin Rush. James Buchanan, later president, lived here.

title: Asa Packer Mansion
desc: Designed by Samuel Sloan, home of Asa Packer, founder of the Lehigh Valley Railroad and Lehigh University.

title: Pennsylvania State Capitol Complex
desc: Includes the Pennsylvania State Capitol, North and South Office Buildings, Finance Building, Forum Building, State Street Bridge and Ryan Legislative Office Building. Originally listed with only the capitol, expanded in 2013 to encompass surrounding buildings.

title: Gifford Pinchot House
desc: Home of Gifford Pinchot, first head of the U.S. Forest Service and two-time state governor.

title: Terence V. Powderly House
desc: Longtime home of Terence Vincent Powderly, a Knights of Labor leader.

title: Joseph Priestley House
desc: Stately home of chemist Joseph Priestley, who, disenchanted with England moved here in 1794 and continued his ground-breaking research.

title: The Printzhof
desc: A home of Johan Printz.

title: Matthew S. Quay House
desc: A home of Matthew Stanley Quay, a Republican National Chairman who was campaign manager for Benjamin Harrison's successful presidential campaign.

title: Searights Tollhouse, National Road
desc: Tollhouses built in 1835 as part of the National Road.

title: Schaeffer House
desc: Possibly the only remaining German Weinbauernhaus in America, combining a residence with the production of alcohol.[4]

title: Smithfield Street Bridge
desc: A truss bridge built between 1881 and 1883.

title: Staple Bend Tunnel
desc: The first railroad tunnel in the United States. Regarded as an engineering marvel.

title: Stiegel-Coleman House
desc: House built in parts by owner William Stiegel and then by Robert Coleman.

title: Summerseat
desc: A home of George Clymer, a signer of the Declaration of Independence and the U.S. Constitution.

title: George Taylor House
desc: A home of George Taylor, a signer of the Declaration of Independence.

title: M. Carey Thomas Library
desc: An architecturally significant building on Bryn Mawr College campus.

title: Gen. Friedrich Von Steuben Headquarters
desc: Headquarters of drillmaster Baron Friedrich Wilhelm Ludolf Gerhard Augustin von Steuben who had served Frederick the Great. Now part of Valley Forge National Historical Park.

title: Washington's Crossing
desc: Where George Washington crossed the Delaware River to surprise-attack the British at Trenton in 1776.
county: Bucks, PA and Mercer County, NJ

title: Washington's Headquarters
desc: Part of Valley Forge National Historical Park.

title: Waynesborough
desc: Home of General Anthony Wayne.

title: Conrad Weiser House
desc: A home of Johann Conrad Weiser, who enlisted the Iroquois on the British side of the French and Indian War.

title: Benjamin West Birthplace
desc: Birthplace of Benjamin West who supported artists including Gilbert Stuart and Charles Willson Peale. On campus of Swarthmore College.

title: Woodmont
desc: Designed by William Lightfoot Price for industrialist Alan Wood, Jr.. Father Divine also lived here.

title: Woodville
desc: Home of John Neville, tax collector during the Whiskey Rebellion of 1794.

title: Andrew Wyeth Studio and Kuerner Farm
desc: The Kuerner Farm was the inspiration for more than 1,000 Wyeth paintings over a 64-year period. Listing expanded (and renamed) in 2014 to include the studio of Andrew Wyeth.

title: N. C. Wyeth House and Studio
desc: Home and studio of painter N.C. Wyeth and family. Managed by the Brandywine River Museum.

title: Arzberger Site
desc: Archaeological site of a fortified 15th-century Native American village, believed to be Arikara.

title: Battle Mountain Sanitarium, National Home for Disabled Volunteer Soldiers
desc: Facility built in 1907 to treat veterans suffering rheumatism and/or tuberculosis

title: Blood Run Site
desc: A Native American archaeological site, extending into Iowa

title: Bloom Site
desc: This fortified archaeological site preserves the remains of about 25 rectangular houses dating to c. 1000 CE. The site also once contained several burial mounds, which were later destroyed by cultivation. The site was perhaps occupied by ancestors of the Mandan.

title: Crow Creek Site
desc: Site of a prehistoric Native American massacre circa 1325.

title: Deadwood Historic District
desc: Historic mining town.

title: Mitchell Site
desc: Archaeological site of a prehistoric Mississippian culture village. Open to the public.

title: Molstad Village
desc: A fortified prehistoric village of five circular house rings enclosed by a ditch comprises this archaeological site. It represents a transitional period as the Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara peoples arose from the mixing of Central Plains and Middle Missouri cultural traits.

title: Alkali Ridge
desc: A set of widely-scattered archaeological remains of the earliest forms of Puebloan architecture, representing a period of transition from scattered, pit-style dwellings to a settled agricultural lifestyle. These multi-story buildings and kivas have yielded high-quality ceramics, and form the type location for the Pueblo II period (ca. 10th century - ca. 11th century). Landmark area is shown in red on map.

title: Bingham Canyon Open Pit Copper Mine
desc: The world's first and largest open-pit copper mine, Bingham Canyon was opened in 1904.

title: Bryce Canyon Lodge and Deluxe Cabins
desc: The Union Pacific Railroad built this national park lodge in 1924-1927. The architectural style was used by railroads for lodges across the American west with the encouragement of the National Park Service.

title: Central Utah Relocation Center (Topaz)
desc: One of 10 relocation centers for internment of Japanese Americans during World War II. The internees were mostly from northern California and the San Francisco Bay Area, and included many professional artists.[4]

title: Danger Cave
desc: Archaeological site featuring artifacts of the Desert Culture from ca. 9500 BCE until ca. 500 CE.

title: Desolation Canyon
desc: This remote canyon on the Green River was traversed by John Wesley Powell in 1869. Powell's expedition was sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution.

title: Emigration Canyon
desc: The Mormon pioneers traversed the Wasatch Range through this canyon at the western end of their trail, beginning in 1847. The canyon mouth is the location of Brigham Young's famous quotation "This is the place."

title: Fort Douglas
desc: This US Army post was established in the 1860s to uphold United States authority in the Mormon territories, and to protect overland transportation and communication lines.

title: Mountain Meadows Massacre Site
desc: Site of the controversial 1857 massacre of migrants by Utah territorial militia.

title: Old City Hall
desc: Completed in 1866, the city hall also served as the capitol of the Utah Territory, and was the scene of many tensions between Mormon leaders and the United States.

title: Quarry Visitor Center
desc: Built as part of the National Park Service's Mission 66 program of modern architectural design in the US national parks, this visitor center exemplifies the philosophy of locating visitor facilities immediately at the resource being interpreted. The building was closed due to structural damage from unstable soils in 2006, and extensive works, including construction of a new visitor center, were undertaken.

title: Reed O. Smoot House
desc: The home of Reed Smoot from 1892 to his death in 1941. Smoot was a prominent US Senator best known for advocacy of protectionism and the Hawley-Smoot Tariff.

title: Temple Square
desc: The earthly center of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. Begun in the mid-19th century, the Square's Mormon landmarks include the Salt Lake Temple, the Tabernacle, and the Assembly Hall.

title: Brigham Young Complex
desc: The Beehive House and adjacent Lion House were the residence of Brigham Young from 1852 until his death in 1877. As President of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints at the time of the Mormon settlement of the Salt Lake Valley, Young and his home were pivotal in the development of the Church, Utah, and the American west.

title: Beale Street Historic District
desc: Birthplace of the blues style of music, Beale Street produced significant developments in African-American music and the music of the United States generally. W.C. Handy was a prominent Beale Street figure from when this was a lively district of saloons and theaters.

title: William Blount Mansion
desc: The home of William Blount from 1792 to his death in 1800. A veteran of the Congress of the Confederation and the Constitutional Convention where he represented North Carolina, Blount then became governor of the Southwest Territory, led Tennessee to statehood, and later served in the US Senate.

title: Chucalissa Site
desc: This archaeological mound complex dates from the Walls Phase (approximately 15th century) of the Mississippian period. Its well-preserved historic materials include architecture, flora, fauna, and human skeletal remains.

title: Delta Queen (River Steamboat)
desc: River steamboat.

title: Fort Loudoun
desc: Built by the British in 1756 during the French and Indian War, Fort Loudoun allied with the Cherokee to protect the British southern marches. The fort was surrendered to the Cherokee in 1760, who had turned hostile and laid siege to the fort.

title: Fort Pillow
desc: The Confederate victory at the Battle of Fort Pillow (April 1864) ended in the killing of 229 Black Union soldiers out of 262 engaged in the battle. This slaughter by the Southern troops under Gen. Nathan Bedford Forrest has been labeled a massacre. "Remember Fort Pillow!" became a battle cry among Black soldiers for the remainder of the Civil War.

title: Franklin Battlefield
desc: At the Civil War Battle of Franklin (November 30, 1864), Maj. Gen. John M. Schofield's Union troops repelled repeated assaults by Confederate forces under Gen. John Bell Hood. The devastating losses sustained helped doom Hood's Army of Tennessee.

title: George Peabody College for Teachers
desc: As the University of Nashville, the college was the first institution to receive support from the Peabody Education Fund, which had been founded by George Peabody to rebuild education in the South after the Civil War. The university began operating as a teachers' college in 1875 and formally changed its name in 1909. It moved to its present location in 1914.

title: Graceland(Home of Elvis Presley)
desc: Graceland was Elvis Presley's home for 20 years starting in 1957, and is intimately associated with his music and career. Presley profoundly influenced American music and culture in the 20th century, and has been inducted into the Rock and Roll, Gospel, and Country Halls of Fame.

title: The Hermitage
desc: This plantation was the home of Andrew Jackson from 1804 until his death. He built the Greek Revival mansion house in 1819. Jackson served as President of the United States from 1829 to 1837.

title: Hiram Masonic Lodge No. 7
desc: Hiram Masonic Lodge No. 7 is the oldest public building in Franklin, the oldest Masonic Hall in continuous use in Tennessee, and in 1830 was the site of the signing of the Treaty of Franklin, which ordered the removal of the Chickasaw people from their eastern homeland to territory across the Mississippi River. President Andrew Jackson opened the meeting personally.

title: Jubilee Hall, Fisk University
desc: Fisk University was founded in 1865 by the American Missionary Association to provide a liberal arts education for Blacks after the Civil War. Completed in 1876, this Victorian Gothic structure is the oldest building on campus.

title: Long Island of the Holston
desc: The Long Island was a sacred council and treaty site among the Cherokee. Daniel Boone began from here to clear the Wilderness Road through the Cumberland Gap in 1775. The island has been heavily transformed by industrial development, and NPS staff recommended withdrawal of National Historic Landmark status in 1996 due to loss of historic integrity.

title: Moccasin Bend Archeological District
desc: This archaeological site on the Tennessee River contains a highly diverse set of Native American remains from the Archaic, Woodland, and Mississippian periods. Spanish artifacts from the 16th century illustrate the early contact period in the Southeast. Earthworks from the Civil War Battle of Chattanooga are also preserved.

title: Montgomery Bell Tunnel
desc: This is the oldest known full-size tunnel in the US. It was built in 1818-1819 by Montgomery Bell to divert water to provide industrial power. Manual drilling was arduous and performed by slaves using tools such as hammers, chisels, and black powder.

title: Mountain Branch, National Home for Disabled Volunteer Soldiers
Old First Presbyterian Church
desc: Architect William Strickland designed this church in the Egyptian Revival style. Beginning his career as an apprentice to Benjamin Henry Latrobe, Strickland was one of the most prominent architects in the United States at the time of his simultaneous work on the church and the Tennessee State Capitol. Built in 1849, the church has been nicknamed "Karnak on the Cumberland," and was his most in-depth application of the Egyptian style.

title: Pinson Mounds
desc: This site, occupied as early as 5000 BCE, consists mainly of mounds constructed during the Middle Woodland Period (ca. 500 B.C. - 500 A.D.).Built here are two temple mounds, one effigy mound, and several other earthworks.

title: James K. Polk House
desc: This house, built in 1816 was the home of future President James K. Polk for several years when he was a young man.

title: Rattle and Snap
desc: This mansion was built in the Greek Revival style by a relative of President James K. Polk, and sports a distinctive Corinthian portico.

title: Rhea County Courthouse
desc: This courthouse was the scene of the Scopes Trial of July 1925, in which teacher John T. Scopes faced charges for including Charles Darwin's theory of evolution in his public school lessons. The trial became a clash of titans between the lawyers William Jennings Bryan for the prosecution and Clarence Darrow for the defense, and epitomizes the tension between fundamentalism and modernism in a wide range of aspects of American society.

title: Ryman Auditorium
desc: This auditorium was the home of the Grand Ole Opry from for 31 years from 1943 to 1974. The Opry, with its live music shows and radio programs, has deeply influenced the development of country music.

title: Siege and Battle of Corinth Sites
desc: The Davis Bridge Battlefield in Tennessee, site of the Battle of Hatchie's Bridge on 5 April 1862, is part of an NHL along with a long list of areas in nearby Mississippi, as the "Siege and Battle of Corinth Sites".

title: Shiloh Indian Mounds Site
desc: This is the largest remaining fortified Mississippian ceremonial mound complex in the Tennessee Valley, including 6 Mississippian temple mounds, one Woodland burial mound, a village site, and a palisade foundation.

title: Sun Record Company
desc: This musical recording studio was established by Sam Phillips in 1952. It was here that he discovered and/or recorded many of the greatest names in rock and roll, including: B.B. King, Howlin' Wolf, Ike Turner, Rufus Thomas, Elvis Presley, Johnny Cash, Jerry Lee Lewis, Carl Perkins, Charlie Rich, and Roy Orbison. Rock and roll was deeply influenced by Phillips' work, and its advent drove profound changes in American music, society, and race relations.

title: Sycamore Shoals
desc: The Treaty of Sycamore Shoals with the Cherokee, signed here in 1775, allowed the United States to acquire 20,000,000 acres (81,000Â km2) of Cherokee land and to promote settlement of present day Kentucky. Sycamore Shoals later served as an Revolutionary War staging area for the 1780 march of the Overmountain Men to victory over British loyalists at the Kings Mountain.

title: Tennessee State Capitol
desc: This fine example of Greek Revival architecture includes four Ionic porticos and a simple, well-proportioned interior. It was built in 1845-1859 under the direction of the noted architect William Strickland.

title: Wynnewood
desc: This was the earliest settlement in Middle Tennessee, and remains today as a group of six log buildings at a sulfur spring. The 1828 main house was a stagecoach inn and residence.

title: X-10 Reactor, Oak Ridge National Laboratory
desc: As the main atomic research facility in the United States, this nuclear reactor pioneered the production of plutonium and, later, medical radioisotopes. Built in 1943, it was the world's first full-scale reactor.

title: Alvin Cullom York Farm
desc: At the 1918 Battle of the Argonne Forest during World War I, Sergeant Alvin C. York distinguished himself with a one-man action that killed 25 enemy soldiers, took 132 prisoners, and captured 35 machine guns. York received the Medal of Honor for this feat, and became even more famous for his refusal to capitalize on the award. He lived at this farm from 1922 until his death in 1964.

title: Nelson W. Aldrich House
desc: Federal-style home of Aldrich, a U.S. Senator and one of the most powerful men in Washington around the turn of the 20th century. Today home to the Rhode Island Historical Society.

title: Arcade
desc: First enclosed shopping mall in U.S., built in 1828.

title: Eleazer Arnold House
desc: Arnold House, 1691.

title: Isaac Bell, Jr., House
desc: First major Shingle-style house

title: Bellevue Avenue Historic District
desc: Mansions, many exemplary of period styles, built here by summer vacationers in late 19th and early 20th centuries.

title: Block Island South East Light
desc: An 1874 Victorian Gothic brick lighthouse.

title: The Breakers
desc: This mansion was built in the 1890s as the summer house of Cornelius Vanderbilt II.

title: Brick Market
desc: Sophisticated Classical-style Colonial building.

title: John Brown House
desc: Georgian home of John Brown, benefactor of Brown University, built in 1786.

title: Chateau-sur-Mer
desc: This 1852 French villa was built for merchant William Shepard Wetmore. It was the first great Newport mansion of the late 19th century.

title: Cocumscossoc Archeological Site
desc: Area around Smith's Castle, one of Rhode Island's oldest houses, built on the site of an early trading post established by Roger Williams.

title: College Hill Historic District
desc: Original 120 acres (30 ha) of Providence as laid out by Roger Williams; today populated by many well-preserved historic homes, Brown University, and Rhode Island School of Design.

title: Corliss-Carrington House
desc: Well-preserved example of an Adamesque-Federal style townhouse from 1812, with decorative wrought iron columns.

title: Crescent Park Looff Carousel
desc: Well-preserved, working carousel by Charles I.D. Looff from 1895; extremely detailed workmanship.

title: The Elms
desc: Summer "cottage" and estate of Edward J. Berwind in Classical Revival style.

title: First Baptist Meetinghouse
desc: Oldest Baptist congregation in the United States, founded by Roger Williams in 1638. The current building dates to 1775.

title: Fleur-de-lys Studios
desc: Collaboration by Sydney Richmond Burleigh and Edmund Willson is a key early work by American Arts and Crafts Movement.

title: Flying Horse Carousel
desc: One of the earliest American carousels still in operation, dating to 1876. The horses are suspended from chains, giving it its name.

title: Fort Adams
desc: Site of fortifications since 1799, most of the extant facilities date to the mid-19th century. Fort Adams was the principal defense site for Narragansett Bay.

title: Gen. Nathanael Greene Homestead
desc: Homestead of American Revolutionary War general Nathanael Greene

title: John N. A. Griswold House
desc: An early work of architect Richard Morris Hunt, this Stick style house was built in 1864 for China merchant John Griswold.

title: Gov. Stephen Hopkins House
desc: Home of Stephen Hopkins, colonial and state governor, signer of the United States Declaration of Independence

title: Hunter House
desc: Its oldest parts dating to 1748, this house is an excellent example of Georgian frame house, with many interior features and original furnishings.

title: Thomas P. Ives House
desc: An Adamesque-Federal style house, built in the early 1800s.

title: Edward King House
desc: This Richard Upjohn-designed Italian villa house was built for a local merchant and was the largest in the city at time of its 1847 completion.

title: Kingscote
desc: 1839 Gothic Revival house by Richard Upjohn was the first summer residence in Newport.

title: Governor Henry Lippitt House
desc: This well-preserved 1865 Italianate villa-style house was built for Governor Henry Lippitt. It is now a house museum, with original interior furnishings by architect Henry Childs.

title: Marble House
desc: Designed by Richard Morris Hunt for William Kissam Vanderbilt, this was one of the earliest Beaux Arts houses in the U.S.; it helped begin the trend of building mansions in Newport.

title: Newport Casino
desc: Early McKim, Mead and White Shingle-style building; also one of the first social clubs to include recreational facilities. Home to International Tennis Hall of Fame.

title: Newport Historic District
desc: A well-preserved collection of colonial-era buildings in central Newport.

title: Nightingale-Brown House
desc: One of the most accomplished great Georgian houses in the country; later contributions by Richard Upjohn and grounds by Frederick Law Olmsted

title: Ocean Drive Historic District
desc: Long road along southern shore of Newport dotted with later, smaller summer homes and seaside views.

title: Old Slater Mill
desc: The first commercially viable textile mill in the United States.

title: Old State House
desc: A well-preserved Georgian public building from colonial era, it served as the meeting place of colonial, and later state, legislatures until the 20th century.

title: Original U.S. Naval War College
desc: Includes the Naval War College Museum, built in the 1820s as Newport's poorhouse and later donated to the Navy as the first building of the Naval War College, and Luce Hall, the college's first purpose-built building.

title: Redwood Library
desc: Founded in 1747, this library is the oldest to still occupy its original facilities.

title: Joseph Reynolds House
desc: The oldest known three-story timber frame house in New England, built in 1700, it was used as headquarters by Lafayette during the Rhode Island campaign in 1778.

title: William Watts Sherman House
desc: This house was built for banker William Watts Sherman by H. H. Richardson in 1875, and is recognized as a prototype of the Shingle style of architecture.

title: Site of Battle of Rhode Island
desc: Site of the 1778 Battle of Rhode Island, a successful defense of Aquidneck Island by British forces in the American Revolutionary War.

title: Gilbert Stuart Birthplace
desc: Birthplace of noted portraitist Gilbert Stuart.

title: Trinity Church
desc: Oldest parish church in Rhode Island; its early 18th-century design is modeled on Boston's Old North Church.

title: University Hall, Brown University
desc: This first building on the Brown University campus, built in 1770.

title: Vernon House
desc: Sophisticated Georgian frame home used as headquarters by Rochambeau during the American Revolutionary War.

title: Wanton-Lyman-Hazard House
desc: Built circa 1697, this is the oldest house in Newport, illustrating the transition from 17th to 18th-century architectural styles.

title: Alamo
desc: Former mission and fortress compound; now a museum; built by the Spanish Empire in the 18th century; later used as a fortress in the 19th century; scene of the 1836 Battle of the Alamo

title: Apollo Mission Control Center
desc: NASA control center

title: Bastrop State Park
desc: This park was designed in the 1930s as a showcase of Civilian Conservation Corps work. Its facilities were designed by CCC architect Herbert Maier.

title: Dealey Plaza Historic District
desc: Site of Kennedy assassination and surrounding buildings that are rumored to have held additional assassins.

title: East End Historic District
desc: Galveston's East End was where the city elite built a number of elaborate mansions.

title: ELISSA (Bark)
desc: Tall ship launched in 1877

title: Espada Aqueduct
desc: Built by Franciscan friars in 1731 to supply irrigation water to the lands near Mission San Francisco de la Espada

title: Fair Park Texas Centennial Buildings
desc: Surviving Art Deco buildings from the 1937 Texas Centennial Exposition.

title: Fort Belknap
desc: Key frontier post of the 1850s; now a museum.

title: Fort Brown
desc: Military post of the United States Army in Texas during the latter half of 19th century and the early part of the 20th century

title: Fort Concho
desc: Established as U.S. Army post in 1867; deactivated 1889; comprises most of the original fort

title: Fort Davis
desc: From 1854 to 1891 Fort Davis protected migrants, mail coaches, and freight wagons, and controlled the southern stem of the Great Comanche War Trail and Mescalero Apache war trails.

title: Fort Richardson
desc: This Texas frontier fort was established in 1867 and abandoned in 1878. It was renovated and reopened as a state park in 1973.

title: Fort Sam Houston
desc: Since the 1870s this facility has served as a major military base for the southern United States. It housed Geronimo folllowing his capture, and has been used as the launching point for a variety of military operations.

title: John Nance Garner House
desc: Home of John Nance Garner, Vice President under Herbert Hoover

title: Governor's Mansion
desc: First designated Texas historic landmark, damaged by arson June 8, 2008

title: HA. 19 (Midget Submarine)
desc: Historic I.J.N. Ko-hyoteki class midget submarine; part of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941; grounded and captured

title: Hangar 9, Brooks Air Force Base
desc: Only surviving hangar of 16 builtin at Brooks Air Force Base in 1918. It is now a museum.

title: Harrell Site
desc: A late prehistoric Plains Indian archeological site.

title: Highland Park Shopping Village
desc: Second shopping mall constructed in the U.S.; opened in 1931, and still in operation

title: J A Ranch
desc: Founded by John George Adair and Charles Goodnight, this is still one of the largest ranches in the Texas Panhandle, and remains in the hands of Adair descendants.

title: Lyndon Baines Johnson Boyhood Home
desc: Birthplace, boyhood home, and resting place of President Lyndon B. Johnson

title: King Ranch
desc: Founded in 1853, this is the largest ranch in the United States; it is larger than Rhode Island.

title: Landergin Mesa
desc: This is a major Panhandle culture archeological site.

title: USS Lexington
desc: This Essex-class aircraft carrier, known as "The Blue Ghost", was the fifth United States Naval ship named in honor of the Revolutionary War Battle of Lexington. After service in the Second World War and the Cold War, it is now a museum ship.

title: Lubbock Lake Site
desc: This major archeological site includes evidence from as far back as 10,000BC. The public can view ongoing archeological work at the site.

title: Lucas Gusher, Spindletop Oil Field
desc: The Spindletop Oil Field was in 1901 where the first major oil gusher of the Texas Oil Boom was discovered.

title: Majestic Theatre
desc: This 1929 theater is the largest in Texas and the second largest in the United States.

title: Mission Concepcion
desc: Part of San Antonio Missions National Historical Park, this 1731 Spanish mission was also the site of the 1831 Battle of ConcepciÃ³n, and early action in the Texas Revolution.

title: Palmito Ranch Battlefield
desc: Site of the 1865 Battle of Palmito Ranch, the last major engagement of the American Civil War.

title: Palo Alto Battlefield
desc: Site of the 1846 Battle of Palo Alto, a precipitating event of the Mexican-American War.

title: Plainview Site
desc: A major archeological site known for Plainview point spear tips.

title: Porter Farm
desc: Part of this farm was used as an experimental agricultural farm in the early 20th century. Successful experiments here led to the establishment of the United States Department of Agriculture's Agricultural Extension Service.

title: Presidio Nuestra Senora De Loreto De La Bahia
desc: Chapel and former fortress compound; now a museum; built by the Spanish Empire in the 18th century; also used as a fortress in the 19th century; scene of the 1836 Battle of Goliad and Goliad Massacre

title: Randolph Field Historic District
desc: The historic core of Randolph Air Force Base, this area was established in the 1920s as a training field for military aviators.

title: Samuel T. Rayburn House
desc: Longtime home of United States Speaker of the House Samuel T. Rayburn

title: Resaca De La Palma Battlefield
desc: Site of the 1846 Battle of Resaca de La Palma, fought early in the Mexican-American War.

title: Roma Historic District
desc: A well-preserved 19th century Rio Grande border town.

title: San Jacinto Battlefield
desc: Site of the decisive Battle of San Jacinto, securing the independence of Texas from Mexico.

title: Space Environment Simulation Laboratory, Chambers A and B
desc: This laboratory for testing equipment in space-like environments has been in use since 1965.

title: Spanish Governor's Palace
desc: This early Spanish colonial house was home to aristocratic leaders of the Spanish Texas, and is now a city museum.

title: Strand Historic District
desc: The Victorian downtown of Galveston.

title: USS TEXAS
desc: After seeing action in the First and Second World Wars, this ship was the first United States Navy battleship to become a museum, and the first to be named a National Historic Landmark.

title: Texas State Capitol
desc: The seat of Texas government, construction on this Italian Renaissance Revival building began in the 1870s.

title: Trevino-Uribe Rancho
desc: Fortified house built c. 1830, shortly after San Ygnacio's founding.

title: Woodland
desc: This modest house was the home of Texas leader Sam Houston in the 1840s and 1850s.

title: William Aiken House and Associated Railroad Structures
desc: Structures of South Carolina Canal and Railroad Company, the longest operating railroad in the world in 1833, and home of founder William Aiken

title: Atalaya and Brookgreen Gardens
desc: Landmark combining Atalaya and portions of Brookgreen Gardens associated with artist Anna Hyatt Huntington

title: Bethesda Presbyterian Church
desc: Church designed by Robert Mills

title: William Blacklock House
desc: Adamesque house, possibly designed by Gabriel Manigault

title: Borough House
desc: "The oldest and largest collection of 'high style' pise de terre (rammed earth) buildings in the United States". Across the road from Church of the Holy Cross

title: Miles Brewton House
desc: Fine examples of a "double house" (having four main rooms per floor) in Charleston

title: Robert Brewton House
desc: Charleston's oldest dated "single" house (one room wide, with the narrow end toward the street, and entry centered in long side)

title: Brick House Ruins
desc: Ruins of a plantation house that burned in 1929

title: Burt-Stark Mansion
desc: Where the American Civil War ended.

title: Camden Battlefield
